status_message:
Today is the fifteenth anniversary of a day that changed our world. We honor the fallen, the heroism of the first responders and the grief of a nation. Below are a few images of the "United in Memory" 9/11 Victims Memorial Quilts now on display at the International Quilt Study Center & Museum located on East Campus.

Honoring the Victims. Comforting the World. 
The quilt consists of 143 panels containing personalized blocks for each victim of the terrorist attacks in New York, Washington, D.C., and Shanksville, Pennsylvania. The work of 3,600 volunteers from 18 countries totals more than 15,000 square feet, and the quilt panels have toured the country since late 2002. According to Gammel, the quilt serves as "a healing balm to our wounded spirits and as eternal beacons, reaffirming our respect for life and freedom and inspiring an end to hatred, bigotry, ignorance and intolerance."

For more information visit ‚Ä∫‚Ä∫ http://bit.ly/2cg2C9d

status_message: "Husker Nation's heart is broken today to learn of the loss of Sam Foltz in a tragic car accident. Sam was a kind and thoughtful young man who was a leader on the playing field, in the classroom, and in his community. He was an exemplary student-athlete who grew as a player and as a person on his path to recent completion of his degree in agronomy from the University of Nebraska-Lincoln, and anyone who knew him can testify that he had an enduring influence on those around him. Jane and I observed this just a week ago, at the Uplifting Athletes Road Race in Lincoln, where his joy clearly showed through to his teammates and to children impacted by pediatric brain cancer. All of the UNL family around the world is lifting Sam's family, friends, classmates and teammates up at this time and in the difficult days ahead. Our thoughts and support also go out to our Big Ten colleagues and family at Michigan State as they mourn punter Mike Sadler. Life is precious, especially when taken so young." -Chancellor Green #RIP27
link_name: Chancellor Green statement on death of student-athlete Sam Foltz

When Caroline walked onto campus today, many assumed she was the grandparent of a new student but, she's not; she came to NSE to enroll in classes. Caroline Okelberry, 72, is an English major from South Omaha, she wants to study creative writing and write her own book. Caroline has lived an interesting life, including being homeless, living in seven states and driving cross country in an RV. "I've always wanted to go to college. When I was 15 my dad died, and back in 1959 we didn't have welfare or food stamps. I had to quit school to go to work. I did go back and finish my high school degree later on. Then I was a legal assistant and executive secretary professionally." Welcome to UNL, Caroline. We're honored to have you. #HumansOfNSE 
(Transcript from UNL New Student Experience personal interview).

Congratulations to Matt Waite, professor of practice in the UNL College of Journalism and Mass Communications, who was awarded the 2016 Innovation, Development and Engagement Award from the University of Nebraska system. 

Waite is founder of the Drone Journalism Lab, the first of its kind at a journalism school. Since he joined the faculty in 2011, Waite and his students have used drones to report news in six countries on three continents. He regularly speaks about the legal and ethical complexities of using drones at conferences around the world and is frequently consulted by media organizations about their potential. He also teaches courses in data journalism, web development and the intersection of storytelling and technology. He created an open learning lab for students called Maker Hours, helped develop an interdisciplinary minor in informatics and serves on the Publications Board of the Daily Nebraskan. Waite previously was a hybrid programmer/journalist for the St. Petersburg Times, where he developed PolitiFact, a website that fact checks what politicians say. The site became the first website awarded the Pulitzer Prize in 2009. Before becoming a web developer, Waite was an award-winning investigative reporter.

Kathleen Loach from Omaha, Nebraska graduates this morning with a degree in journalism with a focus in advertising, public relations from the College of Journalism and Mass Communications and a degree in psychology from the College of Arts and Sciences. While on campus, Kathleen was involved in and conducted research for NUSAMS, served on the executive team for Chi Omega, was a rider on the Husker Equestrian Team, competed as a presenter for the National Student Advertising Competition and held two internships at UNL. After graduation, Kathleen is finishing her internship with University Communications and continuing to work at Red Thread Creative Agency, and is most looking forward to starting her own adventure as a young professional. Kathleen says the best thing about being a Husker is, "having access to incredibly talented (and connected) mentors. I don't know where I'd be without them!" Cheers, Kathleen!

Madison Thorn from Phoenix, Arizona graduates this morning with a degree in global studies and minors in Spanish and communication studies from the College of Arts 7 Sciences. While on campus, Madison was involved with Pi Beta Phi fraternity for women and was an active member of Dance Marathon, Spanish club, the National Society of Collegiate Scholars and interned at the Water for Food Institute. After graduation, Madison hopes to teach English abroad and is most looking forward to meeting new people. To Madison the best thing about being a Husker is, "the energy and love you can find all around the world when you encounter another Husker!" Best of luck, Madison!

Aakriti Agrawal from Pune, India graduates this morning from the College of Business Administration with degrees in actuarial science and finance and a minor in mathematics. During her time on campus, Aakriti was the president of the cultural ambassadors and an active member of the Malaysian Student Association. Aakriti was also a mentor for CBA DreamBIG Academy, New Student Orientation Leader and served as an academic advisor for CBA in addition to writing articles for the Daily Nebraskan. Following graduation, Aakriti will pursue a job working in either the actuarial or risk departments at an insurance company. To Aakriti, the best thing about being a Husker is, "the sense of belonging. When I walk around campus, I feel like I belong and I feel people know me. This feeling can never be matched and now that I'm graduating, I feel like I'm leaving home." Best of luck, Aakriti.

Sarah Bigge from Bellevue, Nebraska graduates this morning with a degree in music education from the Hixson-Lied College of Fine and Performing Arts. While on campus, Sarah was an ambassador for FPA, Collegiate Chapter Representative for the National Association for Music, member of Kappa Kappa Psi, and a member of the Cornhusker Marching Band. After graduation, Sarah will pursue teaching high school band and designing marching shows professionally and is most looking forward to creating her own path. Sarah says the best thing about being a Husker is, "being part of such a great community and family on campus." Good luck, Sarah!

Christina Ensign from Circle Pines, Minnesota will be graduating tomorrow with a degree in music theory from the Hixson-Lied College of Fine and Performing Arts. While on campus, Christina was involved in multiple ensembles and served as the president of the Hixson-Lied Undergraduate Advisory Board. Christina's plans after graduation are to continue learning and growing as a composer and performer, with the goal of attending graduate school. Christina says the best thing about being a Husker is, "having a place you can call home." Best of luck, Christina!

Danielle Passaglia from Wheaton, Illinois will graduate Saturday with a degree in architectural engineering from the College of Engineering. During her time on campus, Danielle was involved with ASHRAE, AESLAC, Engineering Ambassadors, and freshman mentorship program. Following graduation, Danielle will be interning at Affiliated Engineers in Chicago and is looking forward to spending time with her family. Danielle says the best thing about being a Husker is, "the sense of community with other Huskers." Go get em', Danielle!
Can't make the UNL 2016 Spring Graduate Commencement ceremony today at 3pm? Watch it live here ‚Ä∫‚Ä∫ http://commencement.unl.edu.

status_message: Kevin Thor from Stanton, Nebraska will be graduating Saturday with majors in management and communications from the College of Business Administration and College of Arts and Sciences. While on campus, Kevin was involved in Omicron Delta Kappa, FCLA, UNL Globetrotters, served as the national secretary for Phi Beta Lambda, and studied with the Semester at Sea program. After graduation, Kevin will intern at Southwest Airlines and in August, will move to Vietnam to serve as a Fulbright Teaching Assistant for 10 months. He says the best thing about being a Husker is, "the community." Way to go, Kevin!

Brittney Merritt from Los Angeles, California graduates today with her master's degree in educational administration with a specialization in student affairs from the College of Education and Human Sciences. While on campus Brittney was a member of the Chancellor's Commission for the status of people of color, Scarlet Guard, Black Graduate Student Association and worked in the Office of the Vice Chancellor for Student Affairs. Following graduation Brittney will continue to work in higher education and inspiring tomorrow's future. Brittney is most looking forward to being a part of the solution and doing something that will make a difference following graduation and says the best thing about being a Husker is, "it's a global network, every trip I've taken since enrolling at UNL I have yet to not meet a fellow husker. It's a small world." Best of luck, Brittney!

Spring Commencement kicks off this afternoon with Graduate Commencement at 3:00pm followed by Undergraduate Commencement Saturday at 9:30. For more details visit ‚Ä∫‚Ä∫ http://commencement.unl.edu/welcome.

Betsy Hardin from McCook, Nebraska will be graduating Saturday with a degree in child, youth and family studies from the College of Education and Human Sciences. While on campus, Betsy was involved with Scarlet Guard, the University Honors Program, Navigators Leadership Team and traveled to India on teaching program through CEHS at the Anubhuti International Residential School. Betsy is most looking forward to narrowing her educational focus in graduate school and pursing her dream job of being a Marriage and Family Therapist. To Betsy the best thing about being a Husker is, "the awesome community I have found here!" Cheers, Betsy!

Daniel Gutman from Omaha, Nebraska graduates Saturday with his Juris Doctor from Nebraska Law. During his time at the University of Nebraska College of Law, Daniel was involved with the Nebraska Law Review where he served as the articles editor and was a member of the National Moot Court team and served as the president of the Equal Justice Society. Following graduation, Daniel will be a judicial law clerk for Judge John Gerrard, Federal District Court for the District of Nebraska. Following graduation Daniel is looking forward to taking a break and a trip to Hawaii before studying for the bar exam and says the best thing about being a Husker is, "without question, the amazing community." Good luck, Daniel!

Cory Peters from Hickman, Nebraska will graduate Saturday with a degree in animal science from the UNL College of Agricultural Sciences and Natural Resources. While on campus Cory was a member of the 2013 UNL Horse Judging Team and Nebraska Beef Industry Scholars and spent three years working in the Loeffel Meat Laboratory on East Campus. After graduation, Cory will start a full time position with Lone Creek Cattle Company as a Data Management Coordinator. Cory is most looking forward to his involvement in the beef industry and says the best thing about being a Husker is, "being involved and surrounded with energetic and highly motivated individuals that are passionate about the future of our community, state, and world." Way to go, Cory!

Roxana Reyes from Michoacan, Mexico graduates Saturday with her Juris Doctor from Nebraska Law. During her time at the University of Nebraska College of Law, Roxana was a senior certified law student in the immigration clinic and member of the Multi-Cultural Legal Society of Women's Law Caucus. After graduation, Roxana will be working with Pesak Law to serve the immigrant population of Nebraska. Roxana is most looking forward to, "passing the July 2016 bar and serving my community, the immigrant population of Nebraska" after graduation. Best of Luck, Roxana!

Katie Painter from Centennial, Colorado will be graduating this afternoon with a master's degree in community nutrition and health promotion. While on campus, Katie was an active member of Alpha Chi Omega, UNL's fitness instructor and held two gradate assistantships in the Department of Nutrition and Health Sciences. After graduation, Katie will return to Colorado and complete her dietetic internship and is looking forward to living close to the mountains. Katie says the best thing about being a Husker is, "the national recognition of quality academics and competitive sports." Best of luck, Katie!

Kristen Reiman from Butte, Nebraska is graduating Saturday with majors in dietetics and nutrition, exercise, and health from the College of Education and Human Sciences. While on campus, Kristen was involved as a FOCUS student leader, the Nutrition and Health Promotion Association, National Society of Collegiate Scholars, UNL Scarlet Guard and worked as a Campus Recreation group fitness instructor and a Husker Sports Nutrition intern. Following graduation, Kristen will be a dietetic intern at Vanderbilt University Medical Center in Nashville, Tennessee. Kristen says the best thing about being a Husker is, "the community you are able to build with individuals who have the same interests, lifestyle and values you do! Though Lincoln seemed like a "big city" when I first moved to college, UNL has a "small town" feel that can truly become your home." Best wishes, Kristen!

Logan Peter from Pender, Nebraska is graduating Saturday with a degree in animal science and minors in engler agribusiness entrepreneurship and agricultural economics from the College of Agricultural Sciences and Natural Resources. While on campus, Logan was involved a Engler Agribusiness Entrepreneurship Scholar, member of the Nebraska Beef Industry Scholars Program, Alpha Gamma Rho Fraternity and studied abroad in New Zealand. After graduation, Logan will be an Independent Sales Representative for Big Iron Online Auctions and is most looking forward to growing his own entrepreneurial endeavors. Logan says the best thing about being a Husker is, "being surrounded by people that are passionate about their grassroot culture." Best wishes, Logan!

Mara Klecker from Sioux Falls, South Dakota will graduate Saturday with a degree in journalism from the UNL College of Journalism and Mass Communications. While on campus, Mara was a Daily Nebraskan reporter and following graduation, Mara will be starting a reporting internship at the Minneapolis Star Tribune. To Mara, the best thing about being a Husker is, "finding a family of great friends that shared my passion for journalism." Way to go, Mara!

Morgan Spiehs from Wood River, Nebraska is graduating Saturday with degrees in journalism and women's and gender studies from the College of Journalism and Mass Communication. While on campus, Morgan was involved in PREVENT, served on the Women's & Gender Studies advisory board, was a photographer for the The Daily Nebraskan, and participated in CoJMC's Global Eyewitness program. After graduation, Morgan plans to pursue graduate school in the areas of Women's and Gender Studies and education and is most looking forward to using her connections and knowledge she's gained during college to improve the lives of others. Morgan says the best thing about being a Huskers is, "being able to break the ice with people of all walks of life with my knowledge of 1990's Nebraska football." Break a leg, Morgan!

Nicci Poehling from Overland Park, Kansas graduates Saturday from the College of Business Administration with a degree in marketing and a minor in communications. As an undergraduate, Nicci's favorite class was marketing communications with Les Carlson as it combined her major and minor in a classroom setting. While on campus, Nicci was involved with Kappa Kappa Gamma sorority and is looking forward to starting her career at Northwestern Mutual as a financial representative after graduation. To Nicci the best thing about being a Husker is, "all of the connections I've made here and the path my diploma will lead me towards." Best of luck, Nicci!

Bryce Hesterman from Grand Island, Nebraska is graduating Saturday with a music education degree from the Hixson-Lied College of Fine and Performing Arts. While on campus, Bryce was involved with American Choral Directors Association, Phi Mu Alpha Sinfonia, and both marching and pep band. Following graduation, Bryce is planning on finding a job teaching music and is most looking forward to the new opportunities and experiences. He says the best thing about being a Husker is, "how everyone supports each other in their different endeavors and being able to experience first hand why there is no place like Nebraska." Best of luck, Bryce!

Marcellus Kipchumba Kipruto from Iten, Kenya will be graduating Friday with a master's in architecture from the UNL College of Architecture. While on campus, Marcellus was a teaching assistant, member of APX Pytheos and a student member of USGBC. After graduation, Marcellus  will work on IDP (Intern Development Program) and ARE (Architect Registration Examination) in preparation for architecture practice licensing both in the United States and in Kenya. Marcellus is most looking forward to venturing into the architectural field and striving for excellence and his favorite thing about being a Husker is, ''UNL is home away from home." Good luck, Marcellus!

Emma DeVries from Lincoln, Nebraska will graduate Saturday with a degree in art and anthropology with a minor in business from the Hixson-Lied College of Fine and Performing Arts. While on campus Emma was an FPA CAST member, member of Alpha Delta Pi sorority and a volunteer for Dance Marathon and Relay for Life. After graduation, Emma will be working at Morrill Hall and Speedway Motor's Museum of American Speed. Emma is most looking forward to practicing her art full time and says the best thing about being a Husker is, "being part of the community on campus." Good luck, Emma!

Stephanie Hernandez from Grand Island, Nebraska will graduate Saturday with a degree in management from the UNL College of Business Administration. While on campus, Stephanie was  a member of Lambda Theta Nu sorority where she served as both the Dean of Prospective Members and Vice President. Following graduation, Stephanie is looking forward to spending more time with her son, Jayden. She says the best thing about being a Husker is "always having support from people who may not even know you."  Best of luck, Stephanie!

Kolin Scheele from Odell, Nebraska is graduating Saturday with a degree in animal science and a minor in agribusiness entrepreneurship from the College of Agriculture and Natural Resources. While on campus, Kolin was involved in the Engler Program, UNL Collegiate Cattlemen, meat judging team, meat eval team, and Block and Bridle. After graduation, Kolin is most looking forward to pursue a career with Suther Feeds of Frankfort, Kansas and is most looking forward to growing his network and taking on new challenges. Kolin says the best thing about being a Husker is,  "getting to be part of the Engler experience." Way to go, Kolin!

Jessica Sierk from South Sioux City, Nebraska is graduating Friday with a PhD in educational studies from the College of Education and Human Sciences. While on campus, Jessica was a member of the Teaching, Learning, and Teacher Education Graduate Student Association. After graduation, Jessica is moving to New York to be an Assistant Professor of Education at St. Lawrence University and is most looking forward to taking a little break after graduation. She says the best thing about being a Husker is, "being part of such a supportive community on campus and beyond." Good luck, Jessica!

Ryan Erdmann from Palatine, Illinois will be graduating Saturday with majors in computer science and mathematics from the College of Arts and Sciences. While on campus, Ryan was involved in the Raikes School Student Advisory Board. Following graduation, Ryan will be working at Microsoft as a software development engineer and is looking forward to having the opportunity to use all the skills he developed throughout his education. Ryan says the best thing about being a Husker is, "all the incredible people I've had the opportunity to meet and learn from during my time at UNL." Way to go, Ryan!

Jillian Frana from Nebraska City, Nebraska will be graduating Saturday with a major in interior design, minors in art and art history from the College of Architecture. While on campus, Jillian was a College of Architecture Ambassador and student mentor. After graduation, Jillian pursue an Associate Interior Designer position at Wilkin's Architecture Design Planning in Kearney, Nebraska. She is most looking forward to landing a job as a commercial interior designer to help improve health, safety and well being of people. Jillian says the best thing about being a Husker is, "the strong sense of community that UNL creates." Go luck, Jillian!

Morgan Holmen from Sioux Falls, South Dakota will graduate Saturday with a degree in speech language pathology from the College of Education and Human Sciences. While on campus, Morgan was involved with the Nebraska Student Speech and Language Hearing Association. After graduation, Morgan will continue her education through the speech language pathology graduate program at UNL and says her favorite thing about being a Husker is, "being part of a community where everyone is united." Cheers, Morgan!

Dakota Lounder from Blair, Nebraska graduates Saturday with a degree in professional golf management and a minor in business. While on campus, Dakota was involved in the PGM student club and intramural sports. After graduation, Dakota will serve as the Head Golf Professional at Drumm Farm Golf Club in Independence, Missouri and is most looking forward to continuing his PGA career. Dakota says the best thing about being a Husker is, "starting a network of fellow PGM students and professionals that will last a lifetime." Congratulations, Dakota!

John Kosch from Lincoln, Nebraska will be graduating Saturday with a degree in music education from the Hixson-Lied College of Fine and Performing Arts. While on campus, John was in the cornhusker marching band, symphonic band, big band, jazz orchestra, jazz combos, University Singers,  Rocktavo, vocal jazz, Big Red Singers backup band, arts ambassador and CAST member. Following graduation, John will be teaching band to grades 4 ‚Äì 12 in Elm Creek, Nebraska. John is most looking forward to developing his skills as an educator to better serve his students and says the best thing about being a Husker is, "having access to consummate professionals in my field of study, skilled colleagues in other colleges interested in collaboration, and a pervasive and overwhelming attitude of excellence shared by all individuals within the University." Way to go, John!

Taylor Hart from Bassett, Nebraska will be graduating Saturday with a degree in agricultural education-leadership and a minor in child, youth and family studies from the College of Agriculture Sciences and Natural Resources. While on campus, Taylor was involved in Nebraska Human Resources Institute, Sigma Alpha Agricultural sorority, and served as a CASNR ambassador. After graduation, Taylor will be a CASNR recruitment associate and is most looking forward to being able to invest in future UNL students. Taylor says the best thing about being a Husker is, "the traditions I have been a part of and the memories I have made with fellow Huskers." Good luck, Taylor!

Tae-woo Kim from Seoul, South Korea will be graduating Saturday with a major in nutrition, exercise, and health science from the UNL College of Education and Human Sciences. While on campus, Tae-woo was a member of the cornhusker marching band, symphonic band, Kappa Kappa Psi, Student Leadership Education Advisory Council, Students Together Against Cancer and was a UNL campus recreation center personal trainer. After graduation, Tae-woo will be working at the UNL campus rec and is most looking forward to expanding his knowledge and experience in the health and wellness field. He says the best thing about being a husker is, "tradition!" Good luck, Tae-woo!

Laura Koch from Hastings, Nebraska will graduate Saturday with a degree in landscape architecture from the UNL College of Architecture. While on campus, Laura was involved in the marching band color guard and leadership team, American Society of Landscape Architects Great Plains, College of Architecture peer mentor and ambassador. Following graduation, Laura is moving to San Antonio, Texas to work at an urban design landscape architecture firm and is most looking forward to making her own, new path. Laura says the best thing about being a Husker is, "Opportunity. If it weren't for this school I wouldn't have gotten this overwhelming support system, it's like a huge second family. Everyone and everything here has led me to discover my purpose and passion in life. Being a Husker gave me everything I needed to pursue my ambitions and prepare me to make my mark on the world when I leave." Best of luck, Laura!

Maggie Clay from Fort Collins, Colorado will graduate Saturday with a degree in mechanical engineering from UNL College of Engineering. While on campus, Maggie participated in the microgravity club and was president of the air and space research club. Maggie interned at NASA's Ames Research Center and Advance Tank and Construction Co., and traveled to Kampala, Uganda to help the Kinawataka Women Initiatives. Following graduation, Maggie is looking forward to the job search and trying something new. She says the best thing about being a Husker is "the community." Good luck, Maggie!

Darren Johnson from Ames, Iowa will graduate Saturday with a degree in actuarial science from the UNL College of Business Administration. While on campus Darren was involved with the Raikes School, cornfed ultimate frisbee, dance marathon, served as the president of the actuarial science club and was on the student advisory board for the Raikes School. Following graduation, Darren will be starting as an actuarial analyst at Wakely Consulting Group. Darren is most looking forward to hiking the Rockies after graduation and says the best thing about being a Husker is, "Husker Football Gameday." Best of luck, Darren.

status_message: After 87 groundbreakings, 14 budget cuts, 71,382 new graduates, two dozen "Perls of Knowledge" videos, nearly $300 million in annual research expenditures, turning State Fair Park into Nebraska Innovation Campus -- and one very interesting semester with Tommy Lee -- Harvey Perlman is nearing the end of his tenure as the University of Nebraska-Lincoln's chancellor. Today the UNL Center for Digital Research in the Humanities will host their second annual 3D Interactive Expo from 3-5 pm in the Adele Hall Learning Commons! 

The event will allow students to explore ancient cities using the head-mounted Oculus Rift, use mobile devices to interact with 3D ceramic models from Mayan burials and learn about 3D visualization programs that allow us to rebuild lost, ancient temples. The expo is free and open to students.

Yesterday we celebrated the opening of the Adele Coryell Hall Learning Commons at a dedication ceremony. The $10 million space, made possible with nearly $7 million in private donations, is designed to accomodate and promote intensive study and scholarly work and is open 24 hours a day. The lab which is part of the Nebraska Water Center and part of the Daugherty Water for Food Institute is  a cutting-edge core research facility located at UNL. Running behind on filing your taxes?  It's ok, you can still fill out the FAFSA. 
1. When asked if you've filed your 2015 tax return, choose the "will file" option.  
2. You'll then be asked for 2015 tax info.  Instead, enter your 2014 tax info to estimate. 
3. Submit your FAFSA. 
4. After you file your 2015 taxes, log in to your FAFSA again and update the financial section with 2016 tax info.  

More details ‚Ä∫‚Ä∫ http://1.usa.gov/1SfN0m8

2015 December Featured Graduate: 
Megan Auringer of Albuquerque, New Mexico graduates Saturday with a degree in construction management from the University of Nebraska-Lincoln College of Engineering. While on campus, Megan was the chapter president of Alpha Delta Pi sorority and was a member of the National Association of Home Builders, Nebraska Women's Leadership Network and served as a Husker Tour Guide. After graduation, Megan has accepted a position as a project engineer with McCarthy Building Companies in Phoenix, Arizona. Megan is most looking forward to, "becoming a UNL alumnae" after graduation and says, "the traditions I have been a part of, the opportunities I have received, and the memories I have made in college are what make me proud to be a Husker. These accomplishments would not have been possible without the University of Nebraska-Lincoln and for that I am forever grateful." Best of luck, Megan!

2015 December Featured Graduate: 
Kaitlin Davis of Lincoln, Nebraska graduates Saturday from the College of Education and Human Sciences with a degree in family and consumer science education. During her time on campus, Kaitlin was a member of the UNL Marching Band and after graduation plans to substitute teach in and around Omaha while working towards getting a job in the Papillion-Lavista School District. Kaitlin is most looking forward to, "building relationships with students and seeing them grow in and out of the classroom" after graduation and says the best thing about being a Husker is, "being able to earn a degree in an emphasis (FACS) that is so incredibly important to students and their future but not available at many colleges or universities." Congrats, Kaitlin!

2015 December Featured Graduate: 
Sam McCarter from Lincoln, Nebraska graduates Saturday with a degree in business administration from the College of Business Administration. While on campus, Sam was a member of UNL Army ROTC and UNL Mock Trial. After graduation, Sam plans to continue to grow his business, Foundations Progressive Learning Center. Inc., and work to make his city and state a better place. Sam is most looking forward to, "becoming a successful entrepreneur and business owner while serving our country as a Nebraska Army National Guard officer" and says the best thing about being a Husker is, "having one of the best work ethics in the world!" Congrats, Sam!

December Commencement exercises start this afternoon with graduate commencement and are followed tomorrow morning with undergraduate commencement. Details about UNL commencement can be found here ‚Ä∫‚Ä∫ http://commencement.unl.edu.

2015 December Featured Graduate: 
Melinda Knuth of Hartford, South Dakota graduates with a degree in horticulture; entrepreneurship/insect science from the college of agriculture sciences and natural resources this weekend. While on campus, Melinda was a member of Phi Mu Sorority, Horticulture Club, Engler Experience, Order of Omega Honor Fraternity, Alpha Zeta Honor Fraternity, and was a CASNR Ambassadors/Campus Host. After graduation, Melinda will head to Walt Disney World Company to intern at the Golden Oak Resort doing Edible Landscapes. Melinda is most looking forward to, "using the knowledge and skills I've learned in classes on the job" after graduation and says the best thing about being a Husker is, "wearing red and being LOUD!" Best of luck Melinda!

2015 December Featured Graduate: 
Olivia Borer of Elgin, Nebraska graduates this weekend with a degree in textiles, merchandising and fashion design and a minor in business. During her time on campus, Olivia was a group fitness instructor at UNL Campus Rec and participated in Newman Center bible study. After graduation, Olivia will be starting a holistic health coaching program through the Institute of Integrative Nutrition. She hopes to take this certification and open her own health coaching practice, helping others heal and lead a healthy life through real food nutrition, exercise, and overall wellness. Olivia will also be working at the UNL Campus Rec centers as the Group Fitness manager, assisting with the group fitness program and teaching high-intensity group fitness classes. Olivia is looking forward to, "living in my own apartment" after graduation and says the best thing about being a Husker is, "the comradery and passion surrounding Husker sports." Congrats, Olivia!

2015 December Featured Graduate: 
Alex Ruybalid of Lincoln, Virginia graduates Saturday with a degree in journalism with an advertising and pr focus. Following graduation, Alex will be the communications director for a non-profit youth center called The BAY. At the BAY, they are rethinking youth outreach by creating communities where young people can create, explore and inspire. These communities are based around skateboarding, art, and music. Alex is most looking forward to, "using what I have learned after graduation. I have had numerous professors who are so passionate about what they teach and it has been an honor to learn from them." To Alex, the best thing about being a Husker is, "the small-town feel of Lincoln. Everyone knows everyone and this provides a launchpad for people to collaborate, share, explore, and dream. It has been so much fun being a part of this Lincoln/Husker community." Best of luck, Alex!

2015 December Featured Graduate: 
Brianna Gentert of Holstein, Nebraska graduates this weekend earning her degree in hospitality, restaurant and tourism management from the College of Education and Human Sciences and a minors in leadership and food science and technology. During her time on campus, Brianna was a member of the National Association of Catering Executives, Campus Night Life and studied abroad in London. Following graduation, Brianna will work full time for Southern Hospitality Ventures, Inc. a franchisee of Raising Cane's as the Operations Services Manager and she is looking forward to not having homework or projects to work on at the end of the day. To Brianna, the best thing about being a Husker is, "the amount of amazing people you get to meet and the opportunities you are presented with throughout your college career. The energy of Memorial Stadium and UNL's campus is an added bonus!" Cheers, Brianna!

2015 December Featured Graduate: 
Ally Waterhouse of Minden, Nebraska graduates Saturday from the College of Public Affairs and Community Service with a degree in criminal justice and criminology. During her time on campus, Ally was involved with UNL Navigators and hopes to attend graduate school after graduation with plans to earn her PhD in criminology and ultimately teach at an R1 university. The best thing about being a Husker to Ally is, "being proud to claim UNL as my alma mater." Congrats, Ally!
Husker Alumni Forever!

2015 December Featured Graduate: 
Brian Klintworth of Seward, Nebraska graduates this Saturday with a degree in business administration from the College of Business Administration. During his time on campus, Brian was the vice president of Beta Alpha Psi, treasurer of the CBA Student Advisory Board and attended Oxford University in part of the Nebraska at Oxford study abroad trip. After graduation, Brian will be starting a full time role as a tax accountant at HBE Becker Meyer Love, a CPA firm in Lincoln. Brian is most looking forward to, "starting my career in public accounting" after graduation and he says the best thing about being a Husker is, "being able to not just take classes here, but to connect, network and build lifelong friendships." Congrats, Brian!

2015 December Featured Graduate: 
Sophie Tatum from LaGrange, Illinois graduates this weekend from the College of Journalism and Mass Communications with degrees in both broadcasting and journalism and minors in political science, economics and national security studies with a concentration in Arabic. During her time on campus, Sophie was a member of Mortar Board, Alpha Omicron Pi, The Daily Nebraskan and held internships with local news stations as well as Anderson Cooper 360, The Situation Room with Wolf Blitzer and CNN Digital Politics. After graduation, Sophie will be moving to Washington, D.C. to work as a News Associate in CNN's Washington Bureau. Sophie is most looking forward to, "being able to use the skills and knowledge I've obtained while at UNL in a job I really enjoy and am passionate about." The best thing about being a Husker to Sophie is, "the amazing network of fellow Huskers you meet and get to know while at UNL." Best of luck, Sophie!

2015 December Featured Graduate: 
Abigail Johnson from Colorado Springs, Colorado graduates Friday from the University of Nebraska College of Law. During her time at Nebraska Law, Abigail was involved with the Women's Law Caucus, the Student Bar Association, Client Counseling Competition Board and the Community Legal Education Project. After graduation, Abigail plans to move to Omaha to pursue a career in public interest and/or family and juvenile law. Abigail is most looking forward to, "spending time with family in Colorado" after graduation and says the best thing about being a Husker is, "cheering at football games in the student section! GBR!" Congrats, Abigail!

2015 December Featured Graduate: 
Dustin Bowder of Lincoln, Nebraska graduates Saturday with a degree in hospitality, restaurant and tourism management from the College of Education and Human Sciences. During his time at UNL, Dustin worked alongside Professor Hamouz planning many college and community catering events. Dustin also attended the Cannes Film Festival and traveled abroad with Professor Jha. After graduation, Dustin will continue to plan events at Gate 25 and Yes Chef! catering while starting his application for graduate school in Dubai at the UAE Academy for Hospitality. Dustin is most looking forward to "traveling" after graduation and says the best thing about being a Husker is, "the amount of opportunities I have been given through my professors." Best of luck, Dustin!

2015 December Featured Graduate: 
Allison Schneider of Malcolm, Nebraska graduates from the College of Engineering on Saturday with a degree in civil engineering and a minor in business administration. While on campus, Allison was involved with the Society of Women Engineers and volunteered at Matt Talbot Kitchen and Outreach. After graduation, Allison will start work at Parsons Brinckerhoff in Lincoln and is most looking forward to, "using my hard-earned degree to build a career in Lincoln and improve the streets and infrastructure." To Allison, the best thing about being a Husker is, "being employable across the country from my education at UNL, but choosing to stay in Nebraska because there's no place like home!" Congrats, Allison!

2015 December Featured Graduate: 
Daniel Wheaton of Cozad, Nebraska graduates Saturday with a degree in journalism from the UNL College of Journalism and Mass Communications. During his time on campus, Daniel was involved with Cornhusker Forensics, Omicron Delta Kappa and The Daily Nebraskan. Starting in January, Daniel will collaborate across the newsroom, bringing data-driven journalism to all parts of San Diego as a graphics and data reporter at the The San Diego Union-Tribune. Daniel is most looking forward to, "using the skills I've learned to try new forms of journalism after graduation." To Daniel, the best thing about being a Husker is, "knowing wherever you go, you can find another Husker and they'll have your back." Congrats and best of luck!

2015 December Featured Graduate: 
Rachel Genrich of Beatrice, Nebraska graduates on Saturday with a degree in speech-language pathology and a minor in education from the UNL College of Education and Human Sciences. While on campus, Rachel was a key member/social chair for the UNL National Student Speech-Language Hearing Association and volunteer for the Walk for Children with Apraxia, the Cochlear Implant Club, Step Up for Down Syndrome, the People's City Mission, Easter Egg Hunt with the Girl Scout Troop #515, and was a mentor for the Miss Amazing Pageant and Communication Partner at the Barkley Center. After graduation, Rachel will attend Kansas State University in pursuit of her master's degree. Rachel is most looking forward to starting masters program after graduation and says, the best thing about being a Husker is, "knowing that even if you are in a room full of strangers, they won't be strangers for long." Best of luck Rachel!

A message from UNL Chancellor Harvey Perlman: 

A screen capture of a Facebook exchange has been circulating on social media, and as common as that is, in this particular case it warrants this note.
 
In this exchange, one person, whose name is listed as Joey Simpson, uses derogatory and racist language. Another person asks:  "Aren't you affiliated with the University of Nebraska-Lincoln?"
 
The answer is no. No one named Joey Simpson is a student, faculty member or on the staff of the University of Nebraska-Lincoln. Further, we condemn the use of such language in any forum as it only serves to communicate disrespect.
 
This is an opportune time to remind all in the university community that you can share matters that you feel need to be elevated or addressed via the TIPS Incident Reporting System. A link to TIPS appears in the footer of every page on the UNL website. 
 
Harvey
 
Harvey Perlman, Chancellor

With moderate heat expected on Saturday, UNL officials are encouraging fans planning to attend Nebraska's football season opener against Brigham Young University to be aware of the dangers of heat and humidity and to take steps to protect themselves.

To prevent heat illness, fans attending Saturday's game should:

‚Ä∫‚Ä∫ Drink lots of water. Avoid drinking liquids that contain alcohol or large amounts of sugar, which cause the loss of more body fluid. Avoid very cold drinks because they can cause stomach cramps.

‚Ä∫‚Ä∫ Minimize direct contact with the sun. Try to rest often in shady areas.

‚Ä∫‚Ä∫ Snack regularly, rather than eating heavy meals. Consider eating light, cool, easy-to-digest foods such as fruit or salads.

‚Ä∫‚Ä∫ Wear loose-fitting, light-colored clothing.

‚Ä∫‚Ä∫ Fans can bring two sealed or empty water bottles (under 20oz) and refill at fountains on the concourses of Memorial Stadium.

2015 Featured UNL August Graduate: Gregory Sullivan from Omaha, Nebraska will graduate with a masters of business administration (MBA) with a specialization in agribusiness on Saturday from the UNL - College of Business. During his time as a graduate student, Gregory was a research assistant and teaching assistant for the Ag Econ department. After graduation, professionally, Gregory plans on growing into a leadership role within a prominent Agribusiness firm. Personally, he plans to finish his quest of stepping foot on all seven continents - five down, two to go! Gregory is most looking forward to, "applying the last 16 months worth of educational effort towards cultivating a career in the field of agribusiness" after graduation. To Gregory, the best thing about being a Husker is, "the immense pride that accompanies wearing the block N as not only a supporter of this school, team, and state, but also as a new member of an extraordinary alumni base." Congratulations, Gregory!

2015 Featured UNL August Graduate: Nikki Novak graduates Saturday with a degree in agribusiness and a minor in marketing from the UNL - College of Business. While on campus, Nikki was a member of the UNL equestrian Team (Western and English) for four years as well as a member of Phi Beta Lambda, the Newman Center intramural basketball team and served as a Pepsi Service Scholar volunteer. After graduation Nikki will be starting a job with Sandhills Publishing and is also looking into obtaining her real estate license. Nikki is most looking forward to, "taking some time to travel and getting back into showing Arabian horses" after graduation and says the best thing about being a Husker is, "being part of such strong tradition that's known for an outstanding fan base and academic diligence." Congratulations, Nikki!

2015 Featured UNL August Graduate: Robert Kokesh of Wagner, South Dakota graduates Saturday with a degree in agronomy from the College of Agricultural Sciences and Natural Resources. During his time on campus, Robert was a Teammates mentor as well a member of the Husker wrestling team. Following graduation, Robert plans to move back to South Dakota and take ownership of his families farm and is looking forward to, "meeting new people and new challenges." To Robert, the best thing about being a Husker is, "the support of the fans." Go Big Red and Best of Luck Robert!

2015 Featured UNL August Graduate: Amanda Robine from Omaha, Nebraska graduates Saturday with a masters of science in community nutrition and health promotion. During her time as a graduate student, Amanda completed the dietetic internship program and was a graduate assistant for the Nutrition department and later the Wellness program. After graduation, Amanda will begin working for UNL Campus Rec as the Wellness Services and Nutrition Education Coordinator. Following graduation, Amanda is most looking forward to, "beginning my career as a Registered Dietitian" and says the best thing about being a Husker is, "gaining instant family/friends just because you're a Husker!" Best of luck, Amanda!

2015 Featured UNL August Graduate: Kevin Bukowski graduates Saturday with a BSD in architecture from the UNL College of Architecture. During his time on campus, Bukowski and fellow teammates were awarded a Silver Award of Honor from the Society of American Registered Architects for the New York 2015 Design Awards. Bukowski was internationally recognized for his Architecture-410 Air Rights project and was selected as one of six winning student teams, along with students from Cornell University and the ETH Zurich. These student teams join a winner's list that includes international architecture firms Perkins+Will, Robert A.M. Stern Architects and NADAAA. Bukowski's Air Rights project was previously recognized as one of four finalists for the SGH/Dri-Design Competition in December 2014. This summer Bukowski has been studying in Hannover, Germany, as an intern with Architekten BKSP for his last semester.  Before that he worked with Omaha architectural firm Min | Day as an undergraduate assistant in Fall of 2014 and an intern with Antunovich Associates in Chicago, IL, during the Summer of 2014. Congratulations, Kevin!

Throwback to 1966 at the Alpha Xi Delta sorority house as members move in and enjoy a Bubble Up! Do you remember your move-in?

2015 Featured UNL August Graduate: Brittanie Witter from Bellevue Nebraska graduates with a degree in theatre (directing/managing) from the Hixson-Lied College of Fine and Performing Arts on Saturday. During her time on campus, Brittanie was involved with Phi Sigma Pi, Nebraska Masquers, Lazzi Improv Troupe and LGBTQAI+. Following graduation, Brittanie will continue to work with the Disney Company, starting her 3rd internship with Disney and is most looking forward to, "moving to Florida and starting my, hopefully long and prosperous, career with the Disney Company." To Brittanie, the best thing about being a Husker is, "the pride and camaraderie." Best of luck, Brittanie!

2015 Featured UNL August Graduate: Will Miller of Culbertson, Nebraska graduates Saturday from the College of Agricultural Sciences and Natural Resources with a degree in animal science. While on campus Will was involved with the Nebraska Agricultural Youth Council, Nebraska Beef Industry Scholars, FarmHouse Fraternity and was a Nebraska 4-H ambassador. Will has already landed a job with Green Plains Inc. in Central City, as a Commodity and DDG Merchandiser Trainee and will also continue to grow his herd of registered Simmental cattle. Will is most looking forward to, "using the connections I made at the University, through different organizations and courses, to help make a larger impact on the agriculture industry and giving back to those organizations that helped me succeed." The best thing about being a Husker to Will is, "becoming well connected with those within your college because of your shared passion for the industry you are a part of, the University and our great state we all call home." Best of luck, Will!

status_message: 2015 Featured UNL August Graduate: Anna Thomas of Yutan, Nebraska graduates this weekend with degree in journalism and emphasis in advertising and public relations from the UNL College of Journalism and Mass Communications. During her time on campus, Anna was involved with Lincoln Berean Church, Dance Marathon, UNL Scarlet Guard, The Daily Nebraskan and the Nebraska University Students Against Modern Day Slavery (NUSAMS). Following graduation, Anna will work as a customer service manager and associate editor for Bulu Box in Lincoln, Nebraska. Anna is most looking forward to, " spending each day working with the awesome crew at Bulu Box and spending more time with my family" after graduation. To Anna, the best thing about being a Husker is, "following in my dad's footsteps and being a Husker alum right beside him! Go Big Red!" Congratulations, Anna!

2015 Featured UNL August Graduate: Christopher Phipps of Paterson, New Jersey will graduate this Saturday with a master's degree in higher education administration. During his time on campus, Christopher was a graduate assistant for Wellness Services at UNL Campus Rec, Husker Athletics life skills assistant, campus church student leader and an on campus DJ. After graduation, Christopher will be working for the non-profit Men with Dreams and work with implementing events in the community. Christopher is most looking forward to, "being free and structuring his own schedule" after graduation and says the best thing about being a Husker is, "the support system." Best of luck, Christopher!

status_message: Let's get this party commenced! Join the University of Nebraska Alumni Association in the Rail Yard for ConGRADuation Party immediately following today's Undergraduate Commencement Ceremony.
1,882 undergraduate degrees are ready to be conferred. This is #UNL2015 undergraduate commencement.

May 2015 Featured Graduate | Allison Laurenzo of Urbandale, Iowa graduates today with a degree in interior design from the College of Architecture. While on campus, Allison was involved in and president of the American Society of Interior Designers and the International Interior Design Association. Allison also sat on the Student Advisory Board for the College of Architecture, was a peer mentor for interior design students and a member of Tau Sigma Delta and Scarlet Guard. After graduation, Allison will be working full-time at an interior design firm in Omaha, while continuing to pursue her passion for set design. Allison is most looking forward to, "sleep and a salary" after graduation and says the best thing about being a Husker is, "getting to be part of the amazing, innovative and supportive community that this University creates." Congrats, Allison!

May 2015 Featured Graduate | Michael Boal, a native of Ankeny, Iowa will be graduating with his Juris Doctor today. During his third year at Nebraska Law, Michael served as the Executive President for the Student Bar Association. Michael also competed in both Nebraska Law moot court competitions, was a member of the Republican Law Students Association and served as chair for the Nebraska Moot Court Board. In addition to his clerkship with the Lancaster County Attorney's Office, Michael served as a student attorney in the Nebraska Law Civil Clinic. It was through this experience that Michael was able to argue before the Eighth Circuit Court of Appeals. After graduation, Michael is moving to Des Moines, Iowa in search of a government/public job. To Michael, the best thing about being a Husker and Nebraska Law is, "that the school provides you a platform to do whatever you want in law school. If that means you want to work all the time and never really be at school, you can do that. If you want to become really involved in student organizations within the school, you can do that. If you take clinic classes, you can enter appearances in real courts for real clients." Best of luck, Michael!

May 2015 Featured Graduate | Givens Price of Houston Texas graduates today with a degree in business administration, specifically accounting and management. While on campus, Givens was a member of the Cornhusker football team since 2011 and participated in several life skills events. Following graduation, Givens will be starting graduate school at UNL and is most looking forward to, "completing as much graduate school as I can while still on scholarship." To Givens, the best thing about being a Husker is, "being surrounded by GREAT people." Congratulations, Givens!

May 2015 Featured Graduate | Grant Ebel of Scribner, Nebraska graduates tomorrow with a degree in journalism with a focus in advertising and public relations as well as broadcasting. While on campus, Grant was an account executive at Jacht Ad Lab and an ambassador for the College of Journalism and Mass Communications. Grant also held internships with HuskerVision and MTV in New York City. After graduation, Grant is most looking forward to, "future career opportunities" and says the best thing about being a Husker is, "knowing you have the support of Husker Nation behind you." Best of luck, Grant!

May 2015 Featured Graduate | Kourtlin Churchman of Ankeny, Iowa graduates tomorrow with a degree in music education. During her time on campus, Kourtlin was involved with Boots & Cats, an all female a capella ensemble, i2choir, the Cornhusker Marching Band, Big Red Singers, University Singers and received a National Association of Teachers of Singing Classical and Musical Theatre soloist award. Following graduation, Kourtlin will be teaching 8th-10th grade choral music in Norwalk, Iowa. Kourtlin is most looking forward to being close to home again after graduation and she is very excited to "get to know all of the hearts of the incredible young adults that I have the privilege of teaching in the Norwalk Community School District." To Kourtlin, the best thing about being a Husker is, "always knowing that you have a home to return to. Nebraska welcomed me even when I didn't know if I wanted to be welcomed yet. Now, I don't think I will ever question whether or not I belong in Lincoln because of the people and experiences that have shaped the person I have become. GBR." Best of luck, Kourtlin!
We're ready for the #UNL2015 Graduate Commencement Ceremony! Can't make it? Watch it via live stream at http://commencement.unl.edu.

May 2015 Featured Graduate | Madeline Rock of Omaha, Nebraska graduates Saturday with a degree in secondary English education. While on campus, Madeline was a resident assistant in Neihardt Hall for three years. As an RA, Madeline sought out a number of campus activities to immerse herself in school culture. Madeline attended many multicultural and diversity education events (MADE), participated in philanthropies and even joined the Soap Carving club. After graduation, Madeline is starting her teaching career at Elkhorn South High School and is most looking forward to, "a lifelong career in the field I love." To Madeline, the best thing about being a Husker is, "the immense amount of opportunities afforded to students." Best of luck, Madeline!
Finals are Finished! Happy Summer Huskers! #UNL

May 2015 Featured Graduate | Lydia Molnar of Ankeny, Iowa graduates tomorrow with a degree in food technology for companion animals and a minor in animal science. While on campus, Lydia was involved with the Food Science club, Scarlet Guard, Navigators and played for the UNL women's Ultimate Frisbee team. Lydia also interned at Nestle Purina and worked for the UNL Chemistry department. After graduation, Lydia will be interning with Nestle Purina in St. Louis in their technical applications treat group working in application research and development. In August, she will be attending the grain science graduate program at Kansas State. After graduation, Lydia is most looking forward to, "meeting new people and gaining more knowledge in the pet food industry." She says the best thing about being a Husker is, "how friendly people are and how willing professors are to take the time to help students out. I have never had a problem asking a professor for help or having a professor take the time to give me advice to help me succeed. I have been able to build a relationship with the faculty and staff. Most of all, I am known by name by faculty at the University of Nebraska and not a number. I am proud to be a Husker. It has been a wonderful four years at the University of Nebraska Lincoln." Congrats, Lydia!

May 2015 Featured Graduate | Cameron Binder of Mequon, Wisconsin will graduate tomorrow with a degree in business administration with a focus on economics. During his time on campus, Cameron was the president of the UNL curling club and even competed at the national tournament finishing 13th, 5th and 11th. Following graduation, Cameron is still deciding between entering the workforce or attending graduate school, and is most looking forward to, "seeing what lies ahead for both me and the friends I've made." The best thing to Cameron about being a Husker is, "the people you have around you. I've been able to travel a good amount during my time in school and it seems like everywhere I go there's someone connected to UNL. I look forward to spreading the Nebraska network in my own way." Best of luck, Cameron!
Heading to #UNL2015 Commencement this weekend? Here are the Marching Orders for graduates. http://bit.ly/1EkIuar

status_message: May 2015 Featured Graduate | Victoria Simonsen of Superior, Nebraska graduates this weekend with degrees in fisheries and wildlife, grassland ecology and management as well as environmental studies. While at UNL, Victoria was involved with the Wildlife club, Range Management club, Soil and Water Resources club, UNL Honors Program and conducted research as part of the UCARE program. After graduation, Victoria will be working in South Dakota over the summer as a field technician on a pronghorn antelope research project and then will pursue a master's degree in applied ecology next fall at UNL. After graduation, Victoria is most looking forward to, "continuing to improve my understanding of wildlife and plant ecology in a more focused study in graduate school." To Victoria, the best thing about being a Husker is, "that you get the benefit of a large university that provides many opportunities for students, but experience a community atmosphere within your college and school where you get to build lasting relationships with your peers and professors." Congrats, Victoria!

May 2015 Featured Graduate | Jordan Scribner of Lincoln, Nebraska graduates this Saturday with a degree a fine art from the Hixson-Lied College of Fine and Performing Arts. While on campus, Jordan was the president of the Hixson-Lied Student Advisory Board, treasurer of the UNL Art League and member of the UNL soap carving club. Following graduation, Jordan is attending graduate school at Savannah College of Art and Design. Jordan is most looking forward to, "having time to paint" after graduation and says the best thing about being a Husker is, "all of the fantastic art on campus and in downtown Lincoln." Best of luck, Jordan.

May 2015 Featured Graduate | Sarah Jo Lambert of Lubbock, Texas graduates on Saturday with a degree in journalism with specialties in advertising and public relations. While on campus, Sarah was involved with the National Student Advertising Competition, Innocent's Society, Chi Omega and the University Health Center Student Advisory Board. Sarah was also a TEDx Speaker, Jacht Ad Lab member and a social media intern at the Lied Center. After graduation, Sarah is flying south to work in Community Affairs and Grassroots at Southwest Airlines in Dallas, Texas. Sarah is most looking forward to, "getting a puppy, not sleeping on a twin bed and applying my degree to governmental communications" after graduation. To Sarah, the best thing about being a Husker is, "that there is a community within a community willing to support you in any endeavor, whether it's a professor helping you get your first internship as a wide-eyed, bushy-tailed freshman or a Nebraska alum you meet who bleeds scarlet and cream even in another state. There's nothing quite like Husker Nation." Congrats, Sarah!

With UNL Commencement this weekend, we're throwing it back to circa 1905-1915 with a group graduation photo outside Arch Hall. 

Photo via UNL Libraries -- University of Nebraska - Lincoln Libraries Archives & Special Collections.

May 2015 Featured Graduate | Julia DeLaRosa of Waco, Texas will graduate Saturday with a degree in secondary foreign language education. During her time on campus, Julia was involved with the UNL Newman Center and FOCUS and was a New Student Enrollment Orientation Leader. Julia also participated in Pi Alpha Chi sorority as well as the University Chorale and City Campus Choir. After graduation, Julia is heading to Brazil to work as an English teaching assistant on a Fulbright grant. Julia is most looking forward to, "traveling abroad to participate in cultural exchange and in knowledge/experience of language and pedagogy" after graduation. To Julia, the best thing about being a Husker is, "the people that surround you and encourage you to pursue an endless set of opportunities." Best of luck, Julia!

May 2015 Featured Graduate | Geof Wright of Overland Park, Kansas graduates this weekend with degrees in architectural engineering (lighting/electrical emphasis) and construction engineering. During his time on campus, Geof was a member of the Durham School director search committee, Architectural Engineering Student Leadership and Advisory Committee, Sigma Lambda Chi Honor Society and Engineers Without Borders (serving as president for two years). Additionally, Geof interned at Johnson Control, Inc. Henderson Engineers, Inc and Commonwealth Electric Company of the Midwest during his time on campus. Following graduation, Geof is off to Europe to participate in two study abroad programs and then will be interning at HGA Architects and Engineers in Minneapolis, Minnesota for the remainder of the summer. Following his internship, Geof will return to Nebraska in the fall to pursue a masters of architectural engineering degree. After graduation, Geof is most looking forward to, "pursuing his MAE degree and learning about different cultures during his time abroad." To Geof, the best thing about being a Husker is, "the passionate teachers, tremendous facilities, Fall Saturdays and Dr. Krause's mustache." Best of luck, Geof!

May 2015 Featured Graduate | Summer (TSHUI MUM) Ha from Petaling Jaya, Malaysia will earn her master of science degree in architecture this Friday from the UNL - College of Architecture. During her time at UNL, Summer had the opportunity to study abroad in Paris with the Paris: Stories in the History & Theory of Design program and was an active volunteer at the American Veterinary Medical Foundation. Following graduation, Summer will be joining OPN Architects for the summer and is most looking forward to, "spending more time with my family." The best thing about being a Husker to Summer is, "we are very united when it comes to football! Go Big Red!" Best of Luck, Summer!

May 2015 Featured Graduate | Shane Kleier of Trumbull, Nebraska will graduate on Saturday with a degree in secondary education from the College of Education and Human Sciences. While on campus, Shane was involved with the UNL Honors Program, Alpha Lambda Delta, Phi Eta Sigma and played intramural sports. After graduation, Shane will be teaching English in Grand Island, Nebraska at Grand Island Senior High. Shane is most looking forward to, "beginning my teaching career" after graduation and says the best things about being a Husker is, "the cohort experience within CEHS." Best of luck, Shane!

May 2015 Featured Graduate | Olivia Adam of Wilcox, Nebraska graduates this weekend with a degree in dietetics and a minor in Spanish. During her time on campus, Olivia was a member of the Innocents Society and Chi Omega. Olivia also volunteered for The Big Event, TEDx Lincoln Youth, Bryan Health and Dance Marathon and was an Honors Ambassador. After graduation, Olivia will be completing a year-long dietetic internship at the Edward Hines VA Hospital in Chicago, Illinois before taking the exam to become a Registered Dietician. Olivia is most looking forward to, "putting the knowledge and experiences I have had at college into practice" after graduation. To Olivia, the best thing about being a Husker is, "being a part of a university that boasts midwest work ethic and hospitality." Best of luck, Olivia!

May 2015 Featured Graduate | Nathan Hubert of Gretna, Nebraska graduates on Saturday with a degree in biology from the University of Nebraska-Lincoln College of Arts and Sciences. While on campus, Nathan was a member of the Campus Recreation Advisory Council, was a physiology lab TA and completed research with Dr. Chad Brassil. Nathan was also a UNL women's basketball practice team player and competed in basketball, football, volleyball and softball intramurals. After graduation, Nathan will be attending dental school and is most looking forward to, "pursuing my goal of becoming a dentist" after graduation. The best thing about being a Husker to Nathan is, "that all Huskers are family." Congrats, Nathan!

May 2015 Featured Graduate | Kayla Klammer of Ainsworth, Nebraska graduates this weekend with a degree in theatre performance and dance. During her time on campus, Kayla performed in many theatre and dance department performances on both the mainstage and in student productions. Kayla was also a member of the Black Masque Chapter of Mortar Board (a senior honorary) and volunteered at a local elementary school. After graduation, Kayla is heading to Minneapolis, Minnesota to begin rehearsals with the National Theatre for Children and will be going on a five-week tour with NTC to North Carolina. Kayla is most looking forward to, "seeing what the world has in store for me" after graduation and says that best thing about being a Husker is, "finding out who you are in the big sea of red!" Break a leg, Kayla!

We're excited to welcome UNL Alumna and Opera singer Barbara Hendricks back to campus. Hendricks will deliver the undergraduate commencement address at Saturday's ceremony. For more information about this weekend's May commencement ceremonies visit ‚Ä∫‚Ä∫ http://bit.ly/1DW224C

May 2015 Featured Graduate | Jessica Remaly of Gretna, Nebraska graduates this weekend with a degree in hospitality, restaurant and tourism management from the UNL College of Education and Human Sciences. During her time on campus, Jessica was involved with the University Honors Program, Honors Ambassadors, University Ambassadors and Navigators Student Ministry. Jessica also interned at Omaha's Henry Doorly Zoo, Disney Contemporary Resorts, Neligh Economic Development Office as well as a handful of UNL offices. After graduation, Jessica will complete a Disney professional internship with Disney Cruise Lines in their Entertainment Operations Department. Jessica is most looking forward to, "getting married!" after graduation and says the best thing about being a Husker is, "knowing that I will find the friendly faces of fellow Huskers no matter where I go." Best of luck, Jessica!

May 2015 Featured Graduate | Faiz Siddiqui of West Chester, Ohio will graduate Saturday with a degree in journalism from the UNL College of Journalism and Mass Communications. During his time on campus Faiz was involved with the Daily Nebraskan, The DailyER, UNL Multicultural Students in Media and was an Omaha World-Herald Fellow. After graduation, Faiz plans to travel for a short time, attend the Hearst Journalism Awards National Championships and the move to Washington D.C. to be an intern on the metro desk of The Washington Post. After graduation, Faiz is looking forward to "having a few weeks to pleasure-read, travel and maybe see a rap concert or two." To Faiz, the best thing about being a Husker is, "the people you meet here!" Congrats, Faiz!

May 2015 Featured Graduate | Brianne Steffensmeier from Bellevue, Nebraska graduates this weekend with a degree in business administration and minors in economics and human rights. While on campus Brianne was involved in Nebraska Human Resources Institute (NHRI), Gamma Pi Beta sorority and was a TA fro AGRI 496 and MRKT 341. Brianne was also a Study Abroad Coordinator for CBA, held a position on ASUN and served as a New Student Orientation Leader and CBA Oxford blogger. Following graduation, Brianna is moving to Oklahoma City to work for Teach for America and will teach high school science to underserved inner-city schools. Brianne is most looking forward to, "moving to a new city and starting my adventure, and challenge myself." The best thing about being a Husker to Brianne is, "being able to receive an incredible education and meet the most amazing friends while here and knowing that no matter where I move, I will always be honored and proud to say that I am a Husker." Best of luck, Brianne!

There are still a few days to decorate your mortar board before #UNL2015 May Commencement. Short on ideas? Check out our Mortar Board designs Pinterest board ‚Ä∫‚Ä∫ http://bit.ly/UNLMortarBoardDesigns

May 2015 Featured Graduate | Bryan Howard of Howell, New Jersey graduates this Saturday with degrees in theatre arts and human behavior (interdisciplinary study) and English. During his time on campus, Bryan was active in the theatre department serving for two years as president and treasurer of Nebraska Masquers and performed in various university theatre mainstage and Theatrix productions. Bryan was also an ambassador for the Hixson-Lied College of Fine and Performing Arts, completed UCARE research for two years, was an honors peer mentor and was a member of the Black Masque Chapter of Mortar Board, a senior national honor society. 

After graduation, Bryan is heading to Waterford, Connecticut for two months to work as a literary intern at Eugene O'Neill Theater Center. Following his internship Bryan will be traveling to Indonesia and work as an English teaching assistant under a Fulbright grant. In his own words, Bryan is most looking forward to, "jumping into wildly new and exciting experiences and beginning my career." To Bryan, the best thing about being a Husker is, "the wide range and number of opportunities at your fingertips and the ways in which peers and professors encourage you to seek them out." Congratulations, Bryan!

May 2015 Featured Graduate | Erin Kinley from Blue Hill, Nebraska graduates Saturday with a degree in Horticulture from the UNL College of Agricultural Sciences and Natural Resources. While at UNL, Erin was a member of the UNL Horticulture Club, Pi Alpha Xi-Alpha and the UNL Garden Gang. After graduation, Erin is moving to the east coast to pursue a master's degree in public horticulture through the Longwood Graduate Program at the University of Delaware. Erin is most looking forward to, "taking the next steps toward a career in connecting people with plants" and says the best thing about being a Husker is, "the opportunity to experience so many different things while in school, from research and student involvement to travel and volunteer work." Best of luck, Erin!

May 2015 Featured Graduate | Courtney Leikam from Lincoln, Nebraska will graduate on Saturday with degrees in both German and global studies from the University of Nebraska-Lincoln College of Arts and Sciences. During her time on campus, Courtney was a member of the UNL Model United Nations for three years and was the co-president this past year. Courtney was also involved with PREVENT and spent time volunteering at the Women's Center. After graduation, Courtney will be moving to Germany to be an English teaching assistant on a Fulbright Scholarship. Courtney is most looking forward to, "moving to Germany" after graduation and says the best thing about being a Husker is, "the sense of community amongst the students." Viel Gl√ºck! Courtney.

May 2015 Featured Graduate | Eddie Walters from Omaha, Nebraska graduates this weekend with a degree in criminal justice from the College of Public Affairs and Community Service. During his time at UNL, Eddie was president of the UNL Campus Rec Advisory Council, VP for UNL Dance Marathon and a member of the Pi Kappa Alpha Fraternity. Following graduation Eddie will be pursuing a career in law enforcement. Eddie is most looking forward to, "traveling" after graduation and says the best thing about being a Husker is "the student body." Go get 'em Eddie!

May 2015 Featured Graduate | Lindsay Spaulding from Canton, Michigan will graduate this weekend with a degree in Psychology from the University of Nebraska-Lincoln College of Arts and Sciences. While on campus Lindsay was a Melvin Jones Learning Community mentor, a New Student Enrollment Orientation Leader and volunteer at the Women's Center and the LGBTQA+ Resource Center. After graduation Lindsay is planning to work in a role with an admissions office or community focused organization. Lindsay is most looking forward to, "creating change by helping one person at a time" after graduation and says, "the best thing about being a Husker is that anyone can find a home here." Best of luck, Lindsay!
