UNL's Winter Commencement Ceremonies were held December 19 and 20 at Pinnacle Bank Arena. 

72 Doctorate degrees and 103 Master degrees were awarded and 855 Baccalaureate degrees. Since its founding in 1869, the University of Nebraska-Lincoln, including today's totals, has awarded 269, 219 degrees.

See other social posts by searching #UNL2014 on popular social media channels. For more information about commencement visit ‚Ä∫‚Ä∫ http://commencement.unl.edu.

December 2014 Featured Graduate - Emily Taylor of Battle Creek, Nebraska graduates today with a degree in agricultural journalism and public relations. During her collegiate career, Emily was a member of the English and western equestrian team and Agricultural Communicators of Tomorrow. After graduation, Emily plans to continue to apply for jobs in the western fashion and or rodeo/equine industry and is most looking forward to not having to open her chemistry book again. The best thing about being a Husker to Emily is, "the pride we take in our football team, Go Huskers!" Best of luck, Emily.

December 2014 Featured Graduate - Danielle Rue of Ralston, Nebraska graduates this weekend with degrees in women's and gender studies and English from the College of Arts and Sciences. While on campus, Danielle was a member of the UNL Honors Program and served as an Honors Program Peer Mentor. Danielle also interned at Lincoln Literacy and the Domestic Violence Council and completed UCARE research on "Women's Studies at UNL: A Brief Digital History." Danielle also presented at the DePauw University 40th National Honors Conference and the UNL No Limits Conference. Following graduation, Danielle will be a program specialist at the Girl Scouts Spirit of Nebraska. After graduation, Danielle is most looking forward to starting her new job and enjoying more free time. The best thing about being a Husker to Danielle is, "building relationships with the university's amazing faculty." Best of luck, Danielle.

December 2014 Featured Graduate - Brianna Foster of Omaha, Nebraska graduates this Saturday with degrees in broadcast journalism and news editorial from the College of Journalism and Mass Communications. During her time on campus, Brianna was a member of the University Program Council, W.E.B. Du Bois Honor Society and Multicultural Students in Media. After graduation, Brianna is most looking forward to a successful journalism career and says the best thing about being a Husker is, "the overall educational and extracurricular experience." Congratulations, Brianna!
Finals are over and it's time to de-stress and enjoy your Winter Break, you've earned it! #UNL

December 2014 Featured Graduate - Katherine Kimble of Cadiz, Ohio will graduate with her JD from the Nebraska College of Law. During her time on campus, Katherine was a member of the Student Bar Association, Big Brothers/Big Sisters program, and volunteered for the Community Legal Education Project. Katherine is also a member of the Delta Theta Phi Law honorary and finishes her degree with a concentration in constitutional law. After graduation, Katherine is looking forward to completing her PhD in social psychology at UNL and spending time with friends and family. The best thing about being a Husker to Katherine is, "the Nebraskan pride that comes with it." Best of luck, Katherine.

December 2014 Featured Graduate - Jake Drozda of Bellwood, Nebraska graduates Saturday with a degree in fisheries and wildlife from the UNL College of Agricultural Sciences and Natural Resources. After graduation, Jake will be entering the U.S. Navy and will working toward being accepted into their pilot program. He is most looking forward to serving his country and continuing to build on the education he received from UNL. Jake is also looking forward to playing an active role in supporting the conservation of the natural resources here in Nebraska and elsewhere. To Jake, the best thing about being a Husker is, "the opportunity to learn and work with professors who are leading novel research in my field." Congratulations, Jake!

December 2014 Featured Graduate - Katelyn Wright of Incline Village, Nevada graduates this weekend from the College of Education and Human Sciences with a degree in textiles, merchandising and fashion design and a minor in business. During her time on campus, Katelyn was an active member of the University of Nebraska Women's Golf Team. After graduation, Katelyn plans to move to Florida to pursue her dream of playing on the LPGA tour and is most looking forward to spending everyday working towards a dream that she has had of playing golf, since she was a little girl. To Katelyn, the best thing about being a Husker is, "the support and amazing group of people that help you in becoming successful." Best of luck, Katelyn!

December 2014 Featured Graduate - Colette Polite of Winnebago, Nebraska will graduate Friday with her PhD in Educational Studies from the College of Education and Human Sciences. While on campus Colette was very active serving on the City of Lincoln Mayor's Multicultural Advisory Committee, UNL TRIO programs, student affairs assessment committee, Zeta Phi Beta sorority and Order of Eastern Star, Elcta Ch. 14. After graduation, Colette plans to continue her teaching career in higher education. Colette is most looking forward to the opportunities ahead of her and plans to help her community. The best thing about being a Husker to Colette is, "the faculty and staff invested in my dream to be a PhD. I join a small but strong community of scholars as a Native American (Northern Cheyenne) PhD." Congratulations, Colette!

December 2014 Featured Graduate - Benjamin Preston from Omaha, Nebraska graduates with a degree in advertising and public relations this weekend from the College of Journalism and Mass Communications. While on campus, Benjamin was the president of PRSSA and served as the PR director for Jacht Ad Lab. Benjamin also completed internships with the Lincoln Children's Museum, Assurity Life Insurance Company and Publicis Healthcare Communications Group. Following graduation, Benjamin will be moving to New York City to work as a global communications associate at Publicis Healthcare Communications Group. Benjamin is most looking forward to moving to New York City and says the best thing about being a Husker is, "knowing I will always have a place to call home." Best of luck, Benjamin!

December 2014 Featured Graduate - Melissa Dragoo of Scottsdale, Arizona graduates this weekend from the College of Business Administration with a degree in supply chain management. During her collegiate career, Melissa was the president of the Supply Chain Management club, member of Delta Sigma Pi business fraternity, Gamma Phi Beta sorority and the Husker Track & Field team. After graduation, Melissa will return to her hometown and plans to work for a manufacturing company. Melissa is looking forward to traveling most after graduation and says the best thing about being a Husker is, "how supportive and genuine the people are." Best of luck, Melissa.

December 2014 Featured Graduate - Brittany Nelson from Osceola, Nebraska will graduate this Saturday with a degree in secondary education from the College of Education and Human Sciences. During her time on campus, Brittany was a member of Gamma Phi Beta sorority, the CEHS advisory board and The UNL Navigators. After graduation, Brittany will joined EDGE Corps and work within The Navigators campus ministry organization and mentor and provide support to women in college. Brittany is most looking forward to living purposely with a passion and says the best thing about being a Husker is, "the friends that surround me while I savor that game day Runza." Best of luck, Brittany!

December 2014 Featured Graduate - Miranda Weldon from Papillion, Nebraska graduates on Saturday with a degree in fisheries and wildlife from the UNL College of Agricultural Sciences and Natural Resources. During her collegiate career, Miranda held an internship at Omaha's Henry Doorly Zoo and Nebraska Wildlife Rehab and In-Sync Exotics Wildlife Rescue. Following graduation, Miranda will begin her career as a Big Cat Keeper at In-Sync Exotics Wildlife Rescue in Wylie, Texas. To Miranda, the best thing about being a Husker is, "I'm a Husker through and through; I'm not just a fan anymore!" Best of luck, Miranda.

December 2014 Featured Graduate - Patrick Hagenbucher of Clive, Iowa will graduate this weekend with a degree in PGA Golf Management and minors in leadership and business communication. During his time on campus, Patrick was both Vice President and President of the PGM student club and also served as a teaching assistant for the program. Patrick was also involved with FOCUS and additional on-campus activities through the Newman Center. After graduation, Patrick will continue to work as an assistant golf professional and he is looking forward to sharing his passion of golf with others and competing in tournaments. To Patrick, the best thing about being a Husker is, "the relationships and connections that he has made during his time at UNL." Go get 'em, Patrick!

December 2014 Featured Graduate - Kaylie Martens of Omaha, Nebraska graduates this weekend from the College of Education and Human Sciences with a degree in nutrition, exercise and health sciences. During her time at UNL, Kaylie was a member of Delta Gamma sorority and was a group fitness instructor at UNL Campus Recreation. Kaylie also had the opportunity to study abroad in Spain. After graduation, Kaylie will start an accelerated nursing school program in Omaha. Kaylie is most looking forward to a long, relaxing vacation in Hawaii after graduation. To Kaylie, the best thing about being a Husker is, "the sense of community on campus, the amazing friendships she has made and cheering on the Huskers on game day!" Go get 'em, Kaylie!

December 2014 Featured Graduate - Nicholas Banks of Omaha, Nebraska will earn a degree in communications from the UNL College of Arts and Sciences. During his time on campus, Nicholas was a member of Omega Psi Phi fraternity, Afrikan People's Union, the Union Board diversity committee and Nebraska College Preparatory Academy. After graduation, Nicholas plans to continue working as a counselor for the Nebraska College Preparatory Academy. Nicholas is looking forward to beginning the next phase of his life after graduation and says the best thing about being a Husker is, "the experience!" Congratulations, Nicholas!

December 2014 Featured Graduate - Rachel Willand-Charnley from Papillion, Nebraska graduates with her PhD in chemistry with an emphasis in organic synthesis this Friday from the College of Arts & Sciences. At UNL Rachel was a preparing future faculty fellow and is preparing to be a postdoctoral research fellow at Stanford University. After graduation, Rachel is most looking forward to beginning her appointment at Stanford and says the best thing about being a Husker is, "learning from the best!" Best of luck, Rachel!

Don't miss the second annual Claire M. Hubbard First Peoples of the Plains Lecture this Friday and Sunday (Oct. 10 &12).
 
The University of Nebraska State Museum welcomes author and educator Virginia Driving Hawk Sneve and attorney Gena Timberman for the second annual Claire M. Hubbard First Peoples of the Plains Lecture on Oct. 10 at the Sheldon Museum of Art.
 
Both speakers are highlighted in the University of Nebraska-Lincoln College of Journalism and Mass Communication's Native Daughters project -- a collection of stories, profiles and multimedia projects about a diverse group of Native American women.
 
In conjunction with the lecture, the International Quilt Study Center and Museum will host free family activities and a Native American quilt exhibit from 1:00-4:00pm on October 12. At 2 p.m., visitors can hear "The Otoe-Missouria Tribe: The Forgotten Nebraskans" from storyteller Matthew "Sitting Bear" Jones in the Reception Hall. For more information visit ‚Ä∫‚Ä∫ http://bit.ly/1xlJvxG

Today is the 13th anniversary of September 11, 2001. Join us tonight for a service and candlelight vigil honoring those who lost their lives and those who are continuing to serve our country. The vigil, hosted by ASUN, will take place at 8 pm on the City Campus Union Plaza. We invite you to take part in honoring our country and those involved with these tragic events.

A chaplain will lead the candlelight vigil/moment of silence and UNL ROTC will present the colors and there will be a 21 gun salute. The Lincoln Fire Department's honor guard will also be in attendance as well as the patriot guard riders.
The C-SPAN Big Ten Bus Tour has arrived on campus! University of Nebraska System Interim President Dr. James Linder is now live on C-SPAN. Stop by the Union plaza at 11 for tours of the bus.

status_message: UNL's August Commencement was conducted at Pinnacle Bank Arena on Saturday, August 16 at 9am. The Commencement speaker was Dr. Susan Sheridan and her speech was titled "Lessons from Preschool." See other social posts by searching #UNL2014 on popular social media channels.
Can't make it to UNL August Commencement? Watch it live: http://real.unl.edu/live_2. Mobile version: http://bit.ly/1oE9utb.

2014 Featured Graduate | Eric Reznicek of Omaha, Nebraska graduates today with degrees in both marketing and finance from the College of Business Administration. During his time at UNL, Eric was the ASUN student body president and student regent as well as a the house manager for his fraternity Farmhouse and was a member of the Honors Program and Mortar Board. Following graduation, Eric will be joining local Lincoln business Hudl as a Technical Lead. After graduation Eric is most looking forward to catching up on sleep and says the best thing about being a Husker is, "Husker Football." Good luck, Eric.

2014 Featured Graduate | Cassandra Rosenthal of Omaha, Nebraska graduates today with degrees in both sociology and psychology from the College of Arts & Sciences. During her undergrad career Cassandra was a member of Alpha Xi Delta Sorority, Scarlet Guard, Campus Impact and was a research assistant for the sociology department and served as a volunteer for Voices of Hope. Following graduation, Cassandra will be working as a Child Behavior Aide at Behaven Kids in Lincoln. Cassandra is looking forward to applying her research from school to her new job as well as making a positive difference in the Lincoln community. The best thing about being a Husker to Cassandra is, "the plethora of opportunities available while attending UNL as well as knowing that no matter where my futures takes me, if theres is a fellow Husker, I will have community." Go get 'em, Cassandra!

2014 Featured Graduate | Melisa Konecky of Wahoo, Nebraska graduates today with degrees in animal science and ag leadership from the College of Agricultural Sciences and Natural Resources. During her time as an undergraduate Melisa was part of the Husker Food Connection as well as Student Involvement. Following graduation, Melisa is looking forward to making a difference and continuing to work in the agriculture industry helping to bridge the gap between farmers and consumers. To Melisa, the best thing about being a Husker is, "the sense of community that comes with being a Husker." Best of luck, Melisa!

2014 Featured Graduate | Shundi Zhan of Quzhou, Zhejiang Province in China graduates today from the college of architecture with a degree in architectural studies. While on campus Shundi was a member of the American Institute of Architecture Students and spent time on an education abroad trip to Germany. Following graduation Shundi is looking forward to applying and attending graduate school. The best thing about being a Husker to him is, "walking around the world with the pride of a Husker." Best of luck Shundi!

2014 Featured Graduate | Cory Soukup of Lincoln, Nebraska graduates this Saturday with a degree in film and new media from the Hixson-Lied College of Fine and Performing Arts. During his time at UNL, Cory had lunch with his best friend weekly, was a member of Cinema 16, participated in the 72-hour film festival and was on the Dean's List for two years. After Saturday, Cory is packing up and heading to Los Angeles to pursue a job as a production assistant on a TV show and plans to climb the ladder to become a writer. The best thing about being a Husker to Cory is, "the Husker community that provides an environment of creativity and support." Break a leg, Cory!

August 2014 Featured Graduate | Austin Gutzmann of Emerson, Nebraska graduates Saturday from the College of Agricultural Sciences and Natural Resources with a degree in applied science. While at UNL, Austin was active in intramural sports and was a trainee with Cargill Ag Sales. After graduation, Austin is looking forward to his future career opportunities and says the best thing about being a Husker is, "the friendly atmosphere on campus." Good luck, Austin!

2014 Featured Graduate | Steven Craig from Hartington, Nebraska graduates Saturday with a degree in Business Administration from the College of Business Administration. While pursuing his degree Steven attended the Nebraska at Oxford program and was a senior counselor for the Cornhusker Boys State camp for four years. Steven also worked in the CBA Help Center and during that time won the CBA Dean's Coin Award, which is presented to individuals who have gone above and beyond to help others in CBA. After graduation Steven will continue to work at Talent Plus in Lincoln and hopes to continue furthering his education through Salesforce and VMware certifications. Steven is also looking forward to continuing to build meaningful relationships after graduation and says the best thing about being a Husker is, "instantly having a common connection with someone." Best of luck, Steven.

2014 Featured Graduate | Yuliana Gallegos Rodriguez of Mexico and San Diego, California will graduate Saturday with her PhD in clinical psychology from the College of Education and Human Sciences. During her time at UNL, Yuliana was involved in the psychology department annual admissions committee, psychological consolations center advisory committee and served as the Nebraska Advocacy Services, Inc.: Consumer Action Research Team Research Coordinator. Following graduation, Yuliana is looking forward to implementing her learned skills in her career. The best thing about being a Husker to Yuliana is, "always belonging to something bigger." Best of luck, Yuliana!

August 2014 Featured Graduate | Steven Cohen of Great Neck, New York graduates from the Hixson-Lied College of Fine and Performing Arts with a degree in music. While at UNL, Steven was active in the UNL orchestra, wind ensemble, Nebraska Alumni Associations's Scarlet Guard, Kappa Kappa Psi and the Association of Students at the University of Nebraska (ASUN). Following graduation, Steven will be taking a week break before pursuing his masters degree in music at UNL. To Steven, the best thing about being a Husker is, "Being a Husker!" Go get 'em, Steven!

August 2014 Featured Graduate | Erika Pfaunmiller of Elizabethtown, Pennsylvania graduates with her doctorate degree in chemistry this Saturday from the College of Arts & Sciences. While on campus Erika was involved in Phi Lambda Upsilon the National Chemistry Honor Society and also served as a graduate representative for student senate. Following Saturday, Erika will be completing a postdoctoral fellowship at UNL. Erika is most looking forward to starting her career after graduation and states the best thing about being a Husker is, "wearing red on game day." Good luck, Erika!

August 2014 Featured Graduate | Linjun Yu of LongYou, China will graduate this weekend from the college of architecture with a degree in architectural studies. While on campus Linjun was active in undergraduate research and studied abroad in Germany. After graduation, Linjun will be attending graduate school and he is looking forward to spending time traveling around the world. The best thing about being a Husker to Linjun is, "the fact that I am a husker!" Good luck, Linjun!

#UNL2014

August 2014 Featured Graduate | Larry Rassan Brown Jr from Chicago, Illinois graduates this Saturday with a degree in broadcasting from the College of Journalism and Mass Communications. During his time at the university, Larry was a member of multicultural students in media and the UNL DJ Club. After graduation, Larry plans to work in a small market to allow him to hone his skills as a multimedia journalist. After graduation, Larry is looking forward to professional opportunities and says the best thing about being a Husker is, "knowing that you're now part of a special group. Not everyone can be a Husker and I am happy to say that I am!" Best of luck, Larry!

#UNL2014

August 2014 Featured Graduate | Kathleen Farris of Omaha, Nebraska graduates this weekend from the College of Agricultural Sciences and Natural Resources and the College of Arts and Sciences with degrees in both biology and fisheries & wildlife as well as a minor in chemistry. While attending UNL, Katie was active on the UNL Women's Rugby team, Sigma Alpha Lambda, a national honors and leadership honors organization, as well as a member of the William H. Thompson learning community. Following graduation Katie will be working in the field as she pursues her master's degree next year. Katie is most looking forward to reading a book for fun after graduation and she thinks the best thing about being a Husker is, "the community and resources available to students." Best of luck, Katie! 

#UNL2014

status_message: Campus Photo of the Day: Ken North, a utilities maintenance technician with UNL's utility services, uses a water cut-off key to test water shutoff valves north of Andrews Hall. North said regular maintenance on the university's underground valves includes removing accumulated rainwater with a wet/dry vacuum, applying grease directly to the valve, testing the valve shutoff and painting metal ground covers. The work is completed to assure that the valve can be turned off in an emergency situation.

Campus photo of the Day: Oliver Simic, a senior UNL horticulture major from Eagle, prepares cultivars for horticulture labs and plant propagation courses in an East Campus greenhouse on June 3. The trees will be used in fall courses at UNL and the University of Nebraska at Omaha. Bill Gustafson, emeritus professor of agronomy and horticulture, is training Simic and other student workers how to prepare the cultivars for classroom use.

2014 May Featured Graduate: Ethan Seagren graduates today from the College of Fine and Performing Arts with a degree in film and new media. While on campus, Ethan was active in student films, interned at Huskervision, completed undergraduate research with the UNL UCARE program and was a member of the Navigators and played intramural sand volleyball and soccer. Following college, Ethan is pursuing a career in visual effects and he is most looking forward to free time after graduation. The best thing about being a Husker to Ethan is, "the incredible opportunities for creativity, research and professional experience." Best of luck, Ethan!

2014 May Featured Graduate: Jana Dietsch of Seward, Nebraska graduates today with a degree in marketing and minor in merchandising from the College of Business Administration. During her career at UNL, Jana was a member of the Big Red Challenge, Campus Rec Advisory Council and served as a student worked in the Office of the Vice Chancellor for Student Affairs. Jana also had a chance to study merchandising and art history abroad in Florence, Italy and was a member of the Nebraska Alumni Association student group Scarlet Guard. After graduation, Jana will be will be working in the marketing industry and is currently in negotiations with two companies. The best thing about being a Husker to Jana is, "the different opportunities that are available to you if you choose to take advantage of them." Best of luck, Jana!

2014 May Featured Graduate: Jane Seu from Omaha, Nebraska graduates today from the College of Arts and Sciences with a degree in political science. During her collegiate career, Jane was a member of the Nebraska Crew Club as well as the Daily Nebraskan. After graduation Jane plans to coach rowing and attend law school. The best thing about being a Husker to Jane is, "having the community of opportunity around you every day!" Best of luck, Jane!

Congratulations to the UNL Class of 2014!

#UNL2014 | #HuskerAlum

2014 May Featured Graduate: Victoria Fry from Tucson, Arizona graduates tomorrow with a degree in chemical engineering from the UNL College of Engineering. While on campus Victoria served as the president of the Society of Women Engineers and was a member of Gamma Phi Beta sorority, Mortar Board, engineering ambassadors and completed research in the the UNL UCARE undergraduate research program. Victoria also had the chance to study abroad in both Costa Rica and France. Following graduation, Victoria will move to San Francisco where she has accepted a position with Technology/Marketing at Chevron. After graduation Victoria is looking forward to sailing in Croatia and the best thing about being a Husker to her is, "being a member of Husker Nation and being connected to a network no matter where you are." Go get 'em Victoria!

2014 May Featured Graduate: Matt Heng of York, Nebraska will graduate this Saturday from the College of Journalism and Mass Communications with a degree in advertising and public relations. While on campus Matt was a member of the University Program Council (UPC), CoJMC Student Advisory Board, UNL Chamber Singers, National Student Advertising Competition and was a student intern for the UNL Office of Career Services. Following graduation Matt plans to travel the hot dog highways of America driving the Oscar Mayer Wienermobile as a Hotdogger/Brand Spokesperson. To Matt, the best thing about being a Husker is the, "on campus community. No matter what interests you have, there's an organization or professor on campus that can help you learn more and get involved." Best of luck, Matt!

2014 May Featured Graduate: Vannina Nkwaya from Rwanda will graduate this weekend with a Bachelor of Science degree in hospitality, restaurant and tourism management. While on campus, Vannina was actively involved in East Campus student involvement and worked at the Food Processing Center. Following graduation, Vannina is planning to start an African lifestyle brand with two of her sisters. The best thing about being a Husker to Vannina is, "being part of something bigger than me, life long held traditions that embody great values of life." Good luck, Vannina!

2014 May Featured Graduate: Whitney Hinshaw of Scottsbluff, Nebraska graduates today with a masters degree in higher education administration. During her time as a graduate student at UNL, Whitney was an instructional programs graduate assistant at UNL Campus Recreation. Following graduation, Whitney is heading to Montana State University to server as the Director of Group Fitness and Instructional Programs in Bozeman, Montana. Whitney is most looking forward to free time and new experiences after graduation and believes the best thing about being a Husker is, "the Husker school spirit." Best of luck in Montana, Whitney.

2014 May Featured Graduate: Caleb Duncan of Cedar City, Utah graduates this weekend with his JD from the University of Nebraska College of Law. While attending law school, Caleb was an intramural staff assistant at UNL Campus Recreation as well as a member of the J. Reuben Clark Law Society and Latter-Day Saints student association. Caleb plans to pass the bar after graduation and looks forward to spending more time with his wife. To Caleb, the best thing about being a Husker is, "being a member of the greatest collegiate family anywhere!" Go get 'em Caleb!

2014 Featured May Graduate: Danae Lenz of Billings, Montana graduates this weekend from the College of Journalism and Mass Communications with a degree in journalism. While on campus Danae was a journalist for the Daily Nebraskan and the Nebraska News Service. Following graduation Danae plans to work as copy editor for a newspaper and is most looking forward to catching up on sleep and camping after graduation. To Danae, the best thing about being a Husker is, "the communities you become involved with. Whether it's an RSO, a job, a sport or a hobby you become a part of, those smaller communities are what make up Husker Nation and what makes being a Husker so fantastic." Best of luck, Danae!
In Case You Missed It, UNL Extension is celebrating their 100th anniversary today!

2014 May Featured Graduate: Meagan Kurmel of Omaha, Nebraska graduates this weekend from the UNL College of Engineering with a degree in architectural engineering with an emphasis in mechanical engineering. While on campus Meagan was involved in the Architectural Engineering Student Leadership Advisory Committee, the Society of American Military Engineers as well as the Society of Women Engineers. Meagan also completed undergraduate research as part of the UCARE program and enjoyed giving back to her community and helping younger people become more interested in STEM programs. Following graduation Meagan will continue her work with the Schemmer Associates in the mechanical engineering department in Omaha and will also be preparing to compete in the Miss Nebraska Czech-Slovak title in June. To Meagan, the best thing about being a Husker is, "the Husker family and cheering on the Huskers especially at football games." Best of Luck, Meagan!

2014 May Featured Graduate: Tyler Sjoberg of Lakeville, Minnesota graduates this weekend with a degree in supply chain management from the College of Business Administration. During his collegiate career, Tyler was the president of the Nebraska Club Baseball team and was a member of the Young Leaders of Supply Chain Management, led campus tours, played intramurals and served on the Sports Club Executive Board. After graduation Tyler is going to be working for Reliant Transportation in Lincoln and he is most looking forward to getting a dog. To Tyler the best thing about being a Husker is, "the memories you get while attending the university and having a great group of friends you will have forever." Best of luck, Tyler!

For 100 years, the University of Nebraska--Lincoln Extension has been providing research-based information to help Nebraska's farmers and ranchers feed the world's growing population.  Looking forward to the next 100!  Learn more at www.extension.unl.edu

2014 May Featured Graduate: Bryce Vaughn of Alliance, Nebraska graduates this Saturday with a degree in Agricultural Economics. While is college Bryce gained real world experience through two unique global internships. He spent  one summer alleviating poverty through purchasing and distributing food to orphans and widows in Mozambique and then returned and worked on the farm bill in Washington D.C with Senator Mike Johanns. After graduation Bryce will be working full-time for Dow AgroSciences at their world headquarters in Indianapolis, Indiana where he is assigned to work on a biotechnology advocacy team where he will work closely with the United States Grains Council, National Corn Growers Association, CropLife America/International, U.S. Farmers and Ranchers and also work with USDA and members of congress in Washington D.C. on biotechnology issues. He is excited to work in agriculture and believes, "agriculture is truly the greatest industry to work in and I am thankful that I will be a part of the movement to educate the world about GMO's and biotechnology possibilities." Best of luck, Bryce!

2014 May Featured Graduate: Abigail Jameson from Grand Island, Nebraska will graduate this Saturday with a degree in nutrition and health sciences from the UNL College of Education and Human Sciences. Abby was actively involved during her undergraduate career spending time as a William H. Thompson Scholar mentor, research assistant at UNMC, as well as a teaching assistant at both UNL and LPS. Abby was a member of UNL's Mortar Board and served as the Selections Chair. Following graduation Abby will spend 9-months in Indonesia on a Fulbright Scholarship and is looking forward to teaching English while there. The best thing about being a Husker to Abby is, "being a citizen of Husker Nation." Best of Luck, Abby!

2014 May Featured Graduate: Ivan Moreno-Hernandez of South Sioux City, Nebraska graduates this weekend with degrees in both chemistry and physics. While on campus, Ivan was the president of the ACS Student Chapter and completed undergraduate research with Dr. Chin Li Cheung and Dr. Martin Centurion. Following graduation, Ivan will be pursuing a PhD in chemistry at Caltech. After graduation Ivan is most looking forward to becoming a scientist and he believes the best thing about being a Husker is, "the helpful colleagues on campus!" Best of luck, Ivan!

2014 May Featured Graduate: Jenna Jaynes of Barlett, Illinois graduates this Saturday with a degrees in broadcasting, journalism and English. During Jenna's UNL career she was actively involved in the Native Daughters: Oklahoma project, Star City News and was a member of the CoJMC Student Advisory Board as well as the National Broadcasting Society. Jenna also served as the Showtune Sundays radio host and looks forward to reporting at a news station after graduation. Jenna is most looking forward to taking over your TV screens after graduation and says the best thing about being a Husker is, "knowing there's a sea of red rooting for you to succeed." Best of luck, Jenna!

2014 May Featured Graduate: Moses Pacheco of Dakota City, Nebraska graduates this weekend from the UNL College of Engineering with a degree in civil engineering. While on campus Moses was involved in the Society of Hispanic Professional Engineers, Sigma Lambda Beta fraternity, Mexican American Student Association and was a McNair Scholar and a member of the Nebraska Preparatory Academy. After graduation Moses plans to pursue a masters of science in civil engineering at Michigan State University and is looking forward to new experiences after graduation. To Moses, the best thing about being a Husker is, "attending a university where you can make a difference in the community as a student." Congratulations, Moses!

2014 May Featured Graduate: Latifa Obaidi from Lincoln, Nebraska graduates this Saturday with degrees in biochemistry and biological sciences. While on campus Latifa was involved with the UNL Honors program and worked on undergraduate research as part of the UCARE program and was also a UCARE and biochemistry ambassador. After graduation Latifa will be attending medical school and looks forward to pursuing her lifelong goal of becoming a doctor and practicing in an underserved community. To Latifa, the best thing about being a Husker is, "always being able to support Husker football." Best of luck, Latifa!

status_message: 2014 May Featured Graduate: Nathaniel Sullivan of Bettendorf, Iowa will graduate from the Glenn Korff School of Music this weekend with a degree in vocal performance. While at UNL Nathaniel was a member of the UNL Opera, Vocal Jazz Ensemble as well as Rocktavo (male a cappella group) and Christian Student Fellowship. After graduation, Nathaniel plans to take a year off and audition for performance opportunities abroad. The best thing about being a Husker to Nathaniel is, "the opportunity to learn from and work with brilliant faculty." Best of luck, Nathaniel!

status_message: 2014 May Featured Graduate: Anna Keiser of Gothenburg, Nebraska graduates this weekend with a degree in merchandising and a minor in marketing with an emphasis in business and entrepreneurship. While on campus Anna was a student ambassador for the National Retail Foundation and was a member of Alpha Xi Delta sorority, Montage, Scarlet Guard, and the Phi Upsilon Omicron academic fraternity. During the summer Anna interned with Kate Spade in New York and following graduation, Anna will be an account manager at VMInnovations. After graduation, Anna is most looking forward to traveling and eventually starting her own business. To Anna, the best thing about being a Husker is, "the school pride and the great friends I have made." Go get 'em, Anna!

If you're near Architecture Hall home of the UNL - College of Architecture, be sure to stop by the 2nd floor and explore the work of masters students in Professor Steve Hardy's design-research studio. 

They have constructed a 7' x 10' model which shows the exiting condition from O to E streets and 4th ‚Äì 10th streets in the South Haymarket area of Lincoln. The model is constructed with the intent of overlaying new roads, bike lanes, and sidewalks, and the blocks are all removable so the possibilities and impacts of the proposed urban strategy and design of individual buildings can be fully communicated.

status_message: Lincoln is becoming quite the destination city, check out this video from University of Nebraska‚ÄîLincoln Conference Services displaying the ever changing Lincoln landscape.

-2013 UNL Featured Graduate- Neil Dufford of Midland, Texas graduated today with degrees in global studies and Russian as well as minors in geography, global security studies and political science. During his time at UNL, Neil was a member of the UNL Golf Team, served as president of the College Republicans and the Student-Athlete Advisory Committee. Following graduation, Neil is moving to the Washington DC area to work as a defense contractor. Neil states the best thing about being a Husker is, "the Husker network across the country." Congratulations, Neil.

-2013 UNL Featured Graduate- Sarah Entzminger from Lincoln, Nebraska graduates today with a degree in electrical engineering. While on campus, Sarah was a member of the Engineering Ambassadors and completed undergraduate research in alternative energy ultimately building a wave tank. Following graduation Sarah will start her career with Burns and McDonnell in Kansas City. Sarah states the best thing about being a Husker is, "no matter where you go, you'll always bleed Husker Red!" Congrats, Sarah!

-2013 UNL Featured Graduate- Brandon Nieveen of Sterling, Nebraska graduates today with degrees in both electrical and computer engineering. During his time on campus, Brandon served as the Delta Upsilon fraternity president and was a member of Mortar Board, NHRI, The Big Event Executive Staff, Order of Omega and Honors Ambassadors. Following graduation, Brandon plays to move to St. Louis to start a job with the "Defense, Space and Security" business unit at The Boeing Company. The BEST thing about being a Husker to Brandon is, "the sense of community. Regardless of where you are, age differences, etc., if two people find out that they are both Huskers, there is a sense of commonality and familiarity between the two." Best of luck, Brandon!

-2013 UNL Featured Graduate- Stephanie Molek of Battle Creek, Nebraska graduates today with degrees in agricultural journalism as well as animal science. During her time at UNL, Stephanie participated in undergraduate research, was the president of Agricultural Communicators of Tomorrow, and a member of Gamma Sigma Delta Honor Society, UNL Honors Program members and a W.H. Thompson Scholar. Stephanie also had a chance to study abroad in England. After graduation, Stephanie will join the Northeast Nebraska News Company as an editor of the Randolph Times newspaper and an agricultural reporter for the company's seven publications. The best thing about being a Husker to Stephanie is, "the network of people and other Huskers who are always there to support you." Congratulations, Stephanie.

-2013 UNL Featured Graduate- Amanda Burau of Lake Hills, Illinois graduates this Saturday with a degree in natural resources and environmental economics. During her time at UNL, Amanda was a member of the Nebraska University Students Against Modern Day Slavery student group as well as a member of the Nebraska's Women's Bowling Team and participant in Dance Marathon. Following graduation, Amanda will work for Teach for America and is looking forward to moving to Denver. The best thing about being a Husker to Amanda is, "the power to inspire." Got get them, Amanda!

-2013 UNL Featured Graduate- Cally Timm from Ravenna, Nebraska graduates this weekend with a degree in fashion merchandising as well as double minors in business and Spanish. While on campus, Cally studied abroad in Valencia, Spain as well as Shanghai, Hangzhou and Beijing China. She was also a member of the Pi Beta Phi Sorority and Montage student group. After graduation, Cally plans to move to Omaha, Nebraska and continue her role as a manager at Kate Spade. The best thing about being a Husker to Cally is, "the opportunity to experience one of the best atmospheres in the nation." Best of luck, Cally!
It's Friday and UNL Finals are over! We hope everyone has a great Winter Break and congratulations to all of our Huskers graduating this weekend. #UNL2013 #UNL

-2013 UNL Featured Graduate- Osama Aljohani from Jeddah, Saudi Arabia graduates this Saturday with a degree in electrical engineering and energy and power systems. Osama was active on campus serving as the president of MSA as well as playing on a championship soccer team. He attributes being active on campus to helping him to adjust to life at UNL in the beginning and with his studies. Following graduation, he is looking forward to spending time with his wife and son. Osama says the best thing about being a Husker is, "the lovely spirit that its people share between each other." Congratulations, Osama!

-2013 UNL Featured Graduate- Sarah Stoltenberg of Cairo, Nebraska graduates this weekend with a degree in fisheries and wildlife and a minor in environmental education. During her time on campus, Sarah was involved in intramural sports, Sigma Alpha and had a chance to study abroad in Puerto Rico. After graduation, she will begin an internship at the Omaha Zoo working with Madagascar animals, jungle animals and penguins! To Sarah, the best thing about SNR is, "the crazy, awesome professors that make class engaging and learning an experience." The best thing about being a Husker is, "being able to say GO BIG RED to anyone wearing a Husker t-shirt wherever you go and being able to strike up a conversation." Best of luck, Sarah!

-2013 UNL Featured Graduate- Jessica Jensen of Springfield, Nebraska graduates this weekend with a degree in advertising and public relations from the College of Journalism and Mass Communications. During her UNL career, Jessica served as the president of UNL's chapter of the Public Relations Student Society of America. Jessica also interned for the Omaha Storm Chasers, United Way of Lincoln and Lancaster County, the University of Nebraska President's Office and with Kiewit Corporate Communications. Following graduation Jessica will continue her Kiewit internship and explore full time opportunities in PR in a nonprofit, corporate or agency setting. To Jessica, the best thing about being a Husker is, "gamedays and the culture everyday!" Best of luck, Jessica.

-2013 UNL Featured Graduate- Jeff Wrage of Valentine, Nebraska graduates this Saturday with a degree in turf grass and landscape management. During his time at UNL, Jeff served as the Vice President of the Turf Club. Jeff is looking forward to beginning his career with the Troon Golf and Desert Forest Golf Club in Carefree, Arizona. To Jeff, the best thing about being a Husker is, "being able to go to internships, conferences, and trips across the country proudly representing the Husker name. I am proud to say that I am a born and bred Husker." Best of luck, Jeff

-2013 UNL Featured Graduate- Tessa Philips from Omaha, Nebraska graduates Saturday with a degree in Civil Engineering from the UNL College of Engineering. During her undergraduate career, Tessa was a member of the UNL Women's Rugby Sports Club, the American Society of Civil Engineers and had a chance to study abroad in both China and Poland. Following graduation, Tessa is heading to Dallas, Texas to work as a Civil Engineer at Kimley-Horn Associates. The best thing about being a Husker to Tessa is, "the support and tradition of Nebraska that I will have my whole life." Best of luck, Tessa!

-2013 UNL Featured Graduate- Katie Frenzen of Fullerton, Nebraska graduates this weekend with a degree in agricultural education-teaching option as well as a minor in agricultural economics. During her undergraduate career, Katie was a member of NHRI, the UNL Agricultural Education Club, UCARE and had the opportunity to travel to China through the International Leadership Seminar for State FFA officers. After graduation, Katie plans to teach agriculture either for UNL Extension or at a high school in a rural community. The best thing about being a Husker to Katie is, "the community of students. Especially within CASNR, there are connections everywhere! Despite the large number of students, there's always a mutual friend somewhere." Best of luck, Katie.
Want to win free tuition to UNL for a semester? Play the game and enter to win a semester's tuition courtesy of Nebraska Crossing Outlet.

Beautiful blue skies in Lincoln today! How are you spending your day? 

Photo via bessielee on Instagram.

-2013 UNL Featured Graduate- Rebecca Roberts from Kansas City, Missouri graduates this Saturday with a degree in family science and minors in education and psychology. During her undergraduate career, Rebecca was a Melvin Jones Scholar as well as an OASIS student, OSAB member and Character Council Member. After graduation, Rebecca plans to study for her Child Family Life Exam and become certified in Child Family Life Education. Rebecca is most looking forward to having free weekends after graduation and states the best thing about being a Husker is, "meeting all the people here! I love that I have made so many connections with so many people and that I know I can always count on these people. Also just knowing that we all have a connection to this place, makes me feel like I am a part of something! GO BIG RED!" Congratulations, Rebecca!

Have you designed your mortar board yet for this weekend's December Commencement? Short on ideas? We have a ton, check them out here on our Pinterest page: http://bit.ly/UNLMortarBoardDesigns. #UNL2013

-2013 UNL Featured Graduate- Josh Mead of Kearney, Nebraska graduates on Saturday with a degree in fisheries and wildlife. During his undergraduate career Josh studied abroad in Puerto Rico, was a member of the 2009-2010 Husker Track and Field Team and worked in the UNL Herpetology Lab. After graduation, Josh is heading to the country of Trinidad to assist on a research project and hopes to pursue an advanced degree in the field of herpetology. Josh states the best thing about being a Husker is, "the sense of community at UNL." Best of luck, Josh!
UNL, we're halfway through Finals Week, WHOOT! WHOOT!

-2013 UNL Featured Graduate- Pakiza Shirinova from Kant, Kyrgyzstan graduates this Friday with a masters in community and regional planning. During her time at UNL Pakiza was involved with the Student Planning Association of Nebraska and the American Planning Association-Nebraska Chapter. Pakiza is most looking forward to continuing her professional career and starting a new chapter in her life. The best thing about being a Husker to Pakiza is, "the spirit of RED!" Congratulations, Pakiza!

-2013 UNL Featured Graduate- Blake Rostine from Hanover Park, Illinois graduates Saturday with a double major in German and political science as well as minors in women's and gender studies and human rights and humanitarian affairs. Blake is most excited about tackling his book list after graduation as well as obtaining his TEFL and teaching English as a second language abroad. The best thing about being a Husker to Blake is, "the fantastic friends I've met and the Nebraskan hospitality." Go get 'em, Blake!

status_message: -2013 UNL Featured Graduate- Paige Ahart from Denison, Iowa graduates this weekend with a double major in athletic training and women's and gender studies and a minor in psychology. Actively involved during her college career, Paige was a member of the Kappa Delta Sorority, Alpha Epsilon Delta Honors Fraternity, Phi Upsilon Omicron Honors Fraternity, the CEHS advisory board and Cather Circle. After graduation, Paige plans to attend physical therapy school and earn a Doctorate in physical therapy. The best thing about being a Husker to Paige is, "the Husker community, No matter where you go, you can find a fellow Husker who is always so welcoming and happy to connect." Best of Luck, Paige!

-2013 UNL Featured Graduate- Derek Niewohner from Scribner, Nebraska will obtain his degree in broadcast production and advertising/PR from the UNL College of Journalism and Mass Communications this weekend. Derek was very active during his undergraduate career serving as a campus visits campus host, intramural sports official and staff assistant for UNL Relay for Life as well as a Marketing and Promotions intern for UNL Campus Rec. After graduation, Derek will return to UNL to pursue his graduate degree. The best thing about being a Husker to Derek is, "the connection you make, the people you meet and the opportunities you have available to you everywhere you go." Congratulations, Derek.
This weekend is UNL 2013 December Commencement at Pinnacle Bank Arena. If you're graduating or cheering on a grad, be sure to use #UNL2013 in your social posts.

-2013 Featured UNL Graduate- Mary Claire Rice from Lincoln, Nebraska graduates this weekend with a degree in textiles, merchandising and fashion design and a minor in art. While on campus Mary was involved in Delta Gamma Sorority, the Order of Omega Honor Society and served as an Honors Program Peer Mentor. Upon graduation Mary is excited to pursue a career in the fashion industry. Mary says the best thing about being a Husker is, "being a fourth generation Husker and participating in the ongoing traditions." Congrats, Mary!

#UNL2013 Featured Graduate: 

Kim Schumacher graduated this weekend with a degree in Hospitality, Restaurant, and Tourism Management with an emphasis in Event Planning and Public Relations and a minor in Leadership and Communication. 

As an undergraduate student, Kim was highly active in Gamma Phi Beta where she served as president, Dance Marathon as a part of the executive team for three years, NHRI as a senior counselor, New Student Enrollment (NSE) as an orientation leader and later student staff member, and Mortar Board as the People Who Inspire Banquet Co-Chair. 

Her involvement in NSE and working with Dr. Tim Alvarez sparked her interest in working with students and helping them find success at UNL. She will be pursuing her master's degree in Educational Administration with an emphasis in Student Affairs this fall. Kim has also been hired as a GA for the Nebraska Alumni Association and will serve as the Nebraska Legends Coordinator to work with 400 incoming freshman. Congrats, Kim!
All #UNL2013 degrees have been awarded! Congratulations UNL graduates and now University of Nebraska Alumni!

#UNL2013 Featured Graduate: 

Kayla Abel graduates today with a degree in Child, Youth and Family studies with a specialization in Family Science. Kayla also completed course work to receive a certificate in Gerontology and a minor in Psychology.

 While at UNL, Kayla was involved with Scarlet Guard and completed more that fifty UNL traditions on campus and was awarded the Official Tradition Keeper medal. She also served on the Scarlet Guard Board of Directors and had the opportunity to study abroad in Brazil. Kayla stated, "I can safely say that my time at UNL was absolutely amazing." Congratulations, Kayla!

#UNL2013 Featured Graduate: 

Cari Johnson from O'Neill, Nebraska graduates Saturday with a degree in Textiles, Merchandising and Fashion Design. Following graduation, Cari plans to continue to gain experience in her field by working at a locally owned boutique and plans to open her own  athletic apparel boutique in the near future. Best of luck, Cari!

#UNL2013 Featured Graduate: 

Kay Kemmet of Bismarck, North Dakota graduates today with a degree in journalism and Spanish. An active member of many UNL organizations, Kay was the president of the CoJMC's student advisory board, wrote for the Daily Nebraskan and studied abroad in Peru. 

Following graduation, Kay is pursuing a career in features and entertainment journalism and looking forward to being a full-time writer. 

To Kay, the best thing about being a Husker is, "the downtown community around UNL and the amazingly supportive professors in the journalism college." Go get 'em Kay!

#UNL2013 Featured Graduate: 

Karen Morris of Crete, Nebraska graduates today with a masters of science with a specialization in Marriage and Family Therapy and a certificate in Medical Family Therapy.

A 16 year non-Hodgkins lymphoma cancer survivor, Karen returned to UNL to pursue her masters degree so she could follow her passion for helping people through illness. Karen stated, "The CYAF Marriage and Family Therapy program has given me the professional knowledge and skills to formally help people and counsel them as they encounter their medical and mental health journeys." Congratulations, Karen!
The red carpet has been rolled out. Congrats to all #UNL students receiving degrees. #UNL2013

#UNL2013 Featured Graduate: 

Haiping Wang of Guangzhou, China graduates today with a Ph.D., Human Sciences with a specialization in child, youth and family studies and a minor in quantitative, qualitative and psychometric methods. 

Haiping states that, "as an international student, I really cherish this learning opportunity and believe the learning and growth gained through the program will forever influence by career and life." Following graduation Haiping will return to China and work as a professor of family studies at East China Normal University. Best of luck to you, Haiping!

#UNL2013 Featured Graduate: 

Sean O'Brien graduates tomorrow from the College of Architecture. During his time at UNL, Sean participated in the American Institute of Architecture Students, the University Honors Program, Alpha Tau Omega Fraternity, College of Architecture Student Ambassadors, Tau Sigma Honors Society, Tau Sigma Delta Honors Society, and Alpha Lambda Delta Honors Society. Sean also participated in a study abroad program in Hannover, Germany, which focused on architecture. Following graduation, Sean will work as an architecture intern at Alley Poyner Maccietto Architects.  After the internship, Sean will begin his Master's of Architecture program. He looks forward to the possibility of using design as a way to help people. Best of luck, Sean!

#UNL2013 Featured Graduate: 

Lorena Carmona from Sutherland, Nebraska graduates on Saturday with degrees in both journalism and broadcasting. While on campus Lorena was the treasurer of Photo Club and Multicultural Students in Media. Lorena also studied abroad in India and was a Omaha World-Herald Fellow. Following graduation Lorena will head to Hastings, Nebraska to work as a morning show producer at KHAS-TV. Lorena stated the best thing about being a Husker is, "the people you meet and the opportunities that are available to you." Congratulations, Lorena!

#UNL2013 Featured Graduate:

Gwyneth U.J. Talley graduates Saturday with FIVE majors.  Her majors include Anthropology, Global Studies, English, History, and Medieval and Renaissance Studies. During her time at UNL Gwyneth was involved in UNL Anthropology Group, Cather Circle, UNL Equestrian Team, UNL Ballroom Dance Team, and Globe Trotters. Gwyneth also participated in four different study abroad programs in Germany and Morocco. Gwyneth is most looking forward to new challenges at UCLA, where she will go to Graduate School in the fall. Gwyneth believes the best thing about being a Husker is the close relationships you build with faculty and staff. Congrats, Gwyneth!

Congratulations to the UNL Class of 2013! We are all very proud of you. We wish you all the best in your next chapter. #UNL2013

Featured Graduate 

Christen Nino De Guzman from Redondo Beach, California graduates today with a degree in advertising and public relations. During her time at UNL, Christen  battled a rare form of cancer and after a strong fight, she won her battle. With her focus on getting real world experience while at UNL, Christen had a variety of internships with organizations such as: Troika Films, Foursquare, Miss America and the Nebraska Medical Center. After graduation, Christen is relocating to Cornelius, North Carolina where she will be working in corporate social media management. She is looking forward to an amazing career with hopes to make Husker Nation proud. Congratulations, Christen! #UNL2013

Featured Graduate

Katie White of Broken Bow, Nebraska is a nutrition science major in the College of Education and Human Sciences and will graduate today with a 4.0 GPA. While at UNL, Katie was a member of the women's cross country and track and field teams. Katie has been recognized for multiple Academic All-Big Ten accolades and was selected as the Wayne Duke Postgraduate Award (one of two student-athletes selected from the Big 10). In addition to competing and pursuing academic excellence, Katie has participated in many community service activities and plans to further her education and become a physical therapist post graduation. Best of luck to you, Katie! #UNL2013

Featured Graduate 

Monica Casey is a fisheries and wildlife major and graduates today. During her time at UNL, Monica was a member of the Delta Delta Delta sorority and served on the CASNR advisory board. Monica was also a peer leader and facilitator for the Reflections body image program at UNL. Monica is most looking forward to saving the world after graduation and will head to Namibia to study southern Africa ecology after graduation. Following her trip to Africa, Monica will begin working as an Environmental Educator for the Hudson River Park in New York, NY. Best of luck, Monica! #UNL2013

Featured Graduate 

Casey Heier is a Biological Systems Engineering major from Columbus, Nebraska. While at UNL, Casey founded and presided over a fraternity and founded and ran the non-profit organization "The World Energy Project" which helps with engineering and humanitarian work in Africa. Casey also studied sustainable energy in Germany and Costa Rica as part of UNL study abroad programs. Following graduation, Casey will attend graduate school at Stanford,  joining their atmospheric energy program in the department of environmental engineering. Congrats, Casey! #UNL2013

OUTDOOR CEREMONIES TODAY CANCELLED

Due to challenging weather this morning, UNL officials have announced the cancellation of outdoor commencement ceremonies.

Graduates and family members are invited to come to the Hawks Center during a specific timeframe (below) so each student can receive his or her diploma from their college dean or associate dean. This will allow each student to be professionally photographed in cap and gown, and for family members to see and take photos of their graduate. Diploma tables will be set up on the Hawks Center indoor field, with college banners to indicate where students will find their dean and be awarded their diploma. 

Parking will be available immediately west of the Hawks Center, in the stadium garage or at the Champions Club. 

The diploma distribution schedule is as follows:

>College of Agricultural Sciences and Natural Resources: 9:45 to 11 a.m.
>College of Architecture: 8 to 9 a.m.
>College of Arts and Sciences: 10 to 11:30 a.m.
>College of Business Administration: 8:30 to 9:30 a.m.
>College of Education and Human Sciences: 9:15 to 11 a.m.
>College of Engineering: 9:45 to 11 a.m.
>Hixson-Lied College of Fine and Performing Arts: 8 to 9 a.m.
>College of Journalism and Mass Communications: 8 to 9 a.m.
>College of Public Affairs and Community Service: 8 to 9 a.m.
Congratulations and best of luck, Devin! #UNL2013

Featured Graduate

Alissa Doerr is an agricultural economics major from Creighton, Nebraska. During her four years at UNL, Alissa had a chance to study abroad in New Zealand, play intramural sports and serve as an ambassador for the College of Agriculture and Natural Resources as well as the Department of Agricultural Economics. Post graduation, Alissa is looking forward to sleeping more before attending the College of Law at UNL this fall. Alissa hopes to one day practice law privately in rural Nebraska. Congrats, Alissa! #UNL2013

Following graduation, Matan plans to obtain a masters in community and regional planning from UNL. Best of luck to you, Matan! #UNL2013

Cameron Bravo is a physics and mathematics major from Raymore, Missouri. While at UNL, Cameron was the president of the Society of Physics Students for two years. On March 3, 2013, the University of Nebraska-Lincoln will host its annual Big Red Road Show at CenturyLink Center in Omaha.

The Big Red Road Show is designed to share UNL's intellectual and student life possibilities with prospective students and the Omaha community. More than 75 interactive booths will honor Nebraska's past through research, academics, and athletics; while sharing the opportunities for student discovery, academic excellence, and student life traditions that shape UNL's future leaders of tomorrow.

With over 75 ways to experience life as a Husker and major prize drawings, this will be the best Big Red Road Show yet! You won't want to miss this exciting event.
Highlights include:

    Talent showcase featuring special performances from schools across the Omaha metro area
    Drawing for a free netbook computer (must be present to win, must be a high school student)
    Drawing for a textbook stipend from University Bookstore to one admitted student
    Free graduation Limousine ride from Old Market Limo to one admitted student
    Free T-shirts to all high school students who visit each exhibit


Big Red Road Show Recognition Tailgate

We're continuing to monitor this winter storm. A decision on closing or re-opening UNL on Friday will be made late Thursday evening or early Friday morning, after an assessment of the storm's intensity and its effects on the university's and city's snow-clearing operations has been made. In the event of a Friday closure, an announcement will be posted at www.unl.edu, and also via local media and the UNL Alert system. To sign up for UNL Alert, go to http://emergency.unl.edu/unlalert.
It's official: UNL is closed Thursday (2/21/2013) due to impending winter storm. All classes and campus operations are cancelled. Be safe, everyone.

GO BIG RED from...

Heroes Game

The matchup between the two schools, to be known as "The Heroes Game," will benefit non-profit organizations doing "incredible good" in the heartland.

Hy-Vee is proud to be the title sponsor of the yearly meeting between the University of Iowa and University of Nebraska football teams ‚Äì a Big Ten Conference rivalry that has been dubbed "The Heroes Game." This annual rivalry benefits the American Red Cross, an organization doing "incredible good" in the heartland.

The "Heroes Game," scheduled for the Friday after Thanksgiving, pits conference powerhouses Iowa and Nebraska in what promises to become an epic battle for bragging rights in the nation's heartland. The two teams will be playing for more than a trophy, however; with the help of Hy-Vee, they will use the national stage created by the game to recognize individuals for acts of heroism in their communities.

In advance of the game, fans of each school will be encouraged to nominate everyday citizens of Iowa and Nebraska who deserve to be honored for extraordinary acts of heroism. One citizen-hero from each state will be invited to attend the game as a special guest of the teams, receive on-field recognition, and have his or her name inscribed on the game trophy.

In addition, UI and NU officials are counting on the intense interest in the big game to help raise money for the American Red Cross as they continue doing heroic work in the two states. Hy-Vee stores in Iowa and Nebraska will spearhead the fundraising effort by creating activities designed to engage and excite fans of each school.


The Heroes Game Presented By Hy-Vee
November 23rd, 2012
Kinnick Stadium
Iowa City, Iowa
Kickoff 11:00 A.M.

status_message:
In honor of all of the men and women who have served in the military, we salute you.

In the fall of 1922, a drive for $430,000 in funds to build a new football stadium was undertaken by faculty, students, alumni and friends of the university. Designed by John Latenser, Sr., a notable Omaha architect, the stadium was named Memorial Stadium to honor all Nebraskans who served in the Civil and Spanish-American Wars and the 751 Nebraskans who died in World War I. Later, the stadium would also honor the 3,839 Nebraskans who died in World War II; the 225 in Korea; and the 422 in Vietnam. Construction was completed in just over 90 working days; Memorial Stadium was dedicated on October 20, 1923.

Inscribed on the four corners of the stadium are the following words, written by former Nebraska professor of philosophy Hartley Burr Alexander:

Southeast: "In Commemoration of the men of Nebraska who served and fell in the Nation's Wars."

Southwest: "Not the victory but the action; Not the goal but the game; In the deed the glory."

Northwest: "Courage; Generosity; Fairness; Honor; In these are the true awards of manly sport."

Northeast: "Their Lives they held their country's trust; They kept its faith; They died its heroes."

Burkhead Bulls No. 13 Huskers Past No. 9 Spartans

Lincoln - Rex Burkhead put on an offensive display with three touchdowns and 157 all-purpose yards to power No. 13 Nebraska to a 24-3 pounding of No. 9 Michigan State at Memorial Stadium on Saturday afternoon.

With the victory, Nebraska improved to 7-1 overall and 3-1 in the Big Ten, while handing the Spartans (6-2, 3-1) their first conference loss of the year. The Huskers pulled even with MSU in the Legends Division standings, while also notching their second win over an Associated Press top-10 team in the past two seasons under Coach Bo Pelini.
Huskers win! 24-3. Great battle with the Spartans. GO B1G RED!!!

status_message:
Erica Peterson is on a path to becoming a doctor. One (or two) degrees at a time. Erica is taking a one-year break from attending medical school at UNMC to earn a master's degree in Public Health from the University of North Carolina-Chapel Hill. (video link below)

Originally from Gothenburg, Neb., Erica is a 2005 graduate of UNL's honors program with degrees in biology and international studies. Erica spent one year after graduation working as a Fulbright Scholar on the prevalence and pathological impact of various species of gregarine parasites in penaeid shrimp which may be indicators of pollutants (heavy metals and organics) in the Gulf of Mexico.

For Spring Break this year, Herbie Husker hit the road. The Nebraska mascot logged over 1,000 miles traveling his favorite state. Surprising students at Bel Air Elementary in Norfolk. Celebrating a Jump Rope For Heart milestone at Westmoor Elementary in Scottsbluff. Breaking ground for a new school in Elm Creek. And cheering on Amherst Elementary for their excellence in reading programs. Herbie also saw the sights along the way. But most of all, Herbie took his road trip to invite all Nebraskans to the Red-White game and to a new website, Nebraska Values  http://nebraskavalues.unl.edu/ .

Husker fans will have their first opportunity to purchase tickets for the 2009 Red-White Spring Game on Wednesday, Feb. 4 beginning at 8 a.m. The game--the first opportunity for the public to get a look at the 2009 Cornhuskers‚Äîwill be played on Saturday, April 18. Kickoff has been set for 1 p.m.

Nebraska fans may purchase tickets on-line at Huskers.com, by phone at 1-800-8-BIG-RED, or in person at the Nebraska Athletic Ticket Office, located in the Stadium Drive Parking Garage. Reserved tickets are $10 each. No television is planned for the game.

For the first time, Nebraska will be selling nearly all of Memorial Stadium on a reserved ticket basis for the spring game. Last year fans could purchase reserved tickets in the East and West Stadium, and after a positive response Nebraska officials have expanded the reserved seating for 2009.
